1
00:00:40,707 --> 00:00:45,212
BOY: <i>"In the decade of the 1930s,
even the great city of Metropolis...</i>

2
00:00:45,379 --> 00:00:49,132
<i>...was not spared the ravages
of the worldwide depression.</i>

3
00:00:49,299 --> 00:00:53,804
<i>In the times of fear and confusion,
the job of informing the public...</i>

4
00:00:53,971 --> 00:00:56,890
... <i>was the responsibility
of the</i> Daily Planet...

5
00:00:57,057 --> 00:01:02,437
<i>...a great metropolitan newspaper,
whose reputation for clarity and truth...</i>

6
00:01:02,604 --> 00:01:07,568
<i>...had become a symbol of hope
for the city of Metropolis."</i>

7
00:06:41,026 --> 00:06:44,154
JOR-EL:
This is no fantasy...

8
00:06:44,321 --> 00:06:47,991
...no careless product
of wild imagination.

9
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:50,827
No, my good friends...

10
00:06:52,162 --> 00:06:58,126
These indictments
I have brought you today...

11
00:06:58,501 --> 00:07:03,506
...the specific charges listed herein
against the individuals...

12
00:07:03,673 --> 00:07:08,303
...their acts of treason,
their ultimate aim of sedition...

13
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:16,978
...these are matters of undeniable fact.

14
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:24,194
I ask you now to pronounce judgment...

15
00:07:24,361 --> 00:07:27,197
...on those accused.

16
00:07:33,536 --> 00:07:35,372
On this...

17
00:07:35,538 --> 00:07:39,876
This mindless aberration,
whose only means of expression...

18
00:07:40,043 --> 00:07:42,295
...are wanton violence and destruction.

19
00:07:45,674 --> 00:07:46,883
On the woman, Ursa...

20
00:07:47,050 --> 00:07:50,637
...whose perversions
and unreasoning hatred of all mankind...

21
00:07:50,804 --> 00:07:54,683
...have threatened even the children
of the planet Krypton.

22
00:08:03,149 --> 00:08:05,694
Finally, General Zod.

23
00:08:06,736 --> 00:08:09,072
Once trusted by this council...

24
00:08:09,239 --> 00:08:12,867
...charged with maintaining the defense
of the planet Krypton itself.

25
00:08:13,034 --> 00:08:15,245
Chief architect
of this intended revolution...

26
00:08:15,412 --> 00:08:21,251
...and author of this insidious plot
to establish a new order amongst us...

27
00:08:21,918 --> 00:08:25,005
...with himself as absolute ruler.

28
00:08:27,424 --> 00:08:29,759
You have heard the evidence.

29
00:08:30,635 --> 00:08:33,096
The decision of the council
will now be heard.

30
00:08:33,263 --> 00:08:34,597
<i>Guilty.</i>

31
00:08:35,557 --> 00:08:37,726
COUNCILMAN:
<i>Guilty.</i>

32
00:08:38,685 --> 00:08:39,936
<i>Guilty.</i>

33
00:08:43,106 --> 00:08:45,233
The vote must be unanimous, Jor-El.

34
00:08:46,192 --> 00:08:48,695
It has therefore
now become your decision.

35
00:08:48,862 --> 00:08:51,197
You alone
will condemn us if you wish...

36
00:08:51,364 --> 00:08:54,284
...and you alone
will be held responsible by me.

37
00:09:03,209 --> 00:09:04,461
Join us.

38
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:09,632
You have been known to disagree
with the council before.

39
00:09:09,799 --> 00:09:12,469
Yours could become an important voice
in the new order...

40
00:09:12,635 --> 00:09:14,554
...second only to my own.

41
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:18,266
I offer you a chance
for greatness, Jor-El!

42
00:09:18,433 --> 00:09:21,561
Take it! Join us!

43
00:09:22,437 --> 00:09:24,814
You will bow down before me, Jor-El.

44
00:09:24,981 --> 00:09:26,274
I swear it.

45
00:09:26,441 --> 00:09:31,321
No matter that it takes an eternity,
you will bow down before me!

46
00:09:31,488 --> 00:09:32,822
Both you...

47
00:09:32,989 --> 00:09:33,990
...and then one day...

48
00:09:34,199 --> 00:09:36,493
...your heirs!

49
00:10:53,987 --> 00:10:55,864
No!

50
00:10:56,030 --> 00:10:59,492
-Let us out of here!
-Help me!

51
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:07,584
URSA: Forgive me!
ZOD: I shall return!

52
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:09,085
Forgive me!

53
00:11:09,294 --> 00:11:11,796
I shall return!

54
00:11:18,136 --> 00:11:20,513
[MACHINERY HUMMING]

55
00:11:27,103 --> 00:11:31,566
An unpleasant duty
has been masterly performed, Jor-El.

56
00:11:31,733 --> 00:11:34,777
They have received the fate
they deserved.

57
00:11:34,944 --> 00:11:37,447
Isolation in the Phantom Zone...

58
00:11:37,614 --> 00:11:40,909
...an eternal living death.

59
00:11:41,117 --> 00:11:44,287
A chance for life, nonetheless.

60
00:11:44,954 --> 00:11:47,081
As opposed to us.

61
00:11:47,790 --> 00:11:51,127
It's suicide. No, it's worse.

62
00:11:51,294 --> 00:11:52,462
It's genocide.

63
00:11:52,629 --> 00:11:54,589
Be warned, Jor-El.

64
00:11:54,756 --> 00:11:59,135
The council has already evaluated
this outlandish theory of yours.

65
00:12:00,303 --> 00:12:04,599
My friends, you know me to be
neither rash nor impulsive.

66
00:12:04,766 --> 00:12:09,771
I am not given to wild,
unsupported statements.

67
00:12:09,938 --> 00:12:13,441
And I tell you that we must
evacuate this planet immediately.

68
00:12:14,442 --> 00:12:17,487
Jor-El, you are one
of Krypton's greatest scientists.

69
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,822
Yes, but so is Vond-Ah.

70
00:12:25,078 --> 00:12:28,831
It isn't that they question your data.
The facts are undeniable.

71
00:12:32,502 --> 00:12:35,964
It's your conclusions
we find unsupportable.

72
00:12:38,258 --> 00:12:43,179
This planet will explode
within 30 days, if not sooner.

73
00:12:43,388 --> 00:12:45,932
I tell you, Krypton
is simply shifting its orbit.

74
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:50,019
Jor-El, be reasonable.

75
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:53,356
My friend...

76
00:12:54,899 --> 00:12:56,526
...I have never been otherwise.

77
00:12:57,193 --> 00:12:58,778
This madness is yours.

78
00:12:58,945 --> 00:13:01,698
This discussion is terminated.

79
00:13:02,198 --> 00:13:05,785
The decision of the council is final.

80
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:30,476
Any attempt by you to create a climate
of fear and panic among the populace...

81
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:34,731
...must be deemed by us
an act of insurrection.

82
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:37,984
You would accuse me of insurrection?

83
00:13:38,401 --> 00:13:41,237
Has it now become a crime
to cherish life?

84
00:13:42,071 --> 00:13:45,575
You would be banished
to endless imprisonment...

85
00:13:45,742 --> 00:13:47,160
...in the Phantom Zone...

86
00:13:47,493 --> 00:13:49,579
...the eternal void...

87
00:13:50,079 --> 00:13:52,915
...which you yourself discovered.

88
00:13:53,833 --> 00:13:58,588
Will you abide by
the council's decision?

89
00:14:03,092 --> 00:14:05,720
I will remain silent.

90
00:14:06,262 --> 00:14:11,768
Neither I, nor my wife
will leave Krypton.

91
00:14:43,466 --> 00:14:45,551
[MACHINERY HUMS]

92
00:14:50,264 --> 00:14:52,308
[KAL-EL CRIES]

93
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:08,491
Have you finished?

94
00:15:11,828 --> 00:15:13,621
Nearly.

95
00:15:18,334 --> 00:15:20,253
It's the only answer, Lara.

96
00:15:20,420 --> 00:15:25,633
If he remains here with us
he will die as surely as we will.

97
00:15:25,800 --> 00:15:27,135
But why Earth, Jor-El?

98
00:15:27,301 --> 00:15:29,971
They're primitives
thousands of years behind us.

99
00:15:30,138 --> 00:15:32,849
He will need that advantage to survive.

100
00:15:35,017 --> 00:15:39,647
Their atmosphere will sustain him.

101
00:15:47,780 --> 00:15:49,699
LARA:
He will defy their gravity.

102
00:15:49,866 --> 00:15:52,326
JOR-EL:
He will look like one of them.

103
00:15:52,702 --> 00:15:54,871
He won't be one of them.

104
00:15:55,037 --> 00:15:56,706
No.

105
00:15:56,873 --> 00:16:00,543
His dense molecular structure
will make him strong.

106
00:16:01,878 --> 00:16:05,882
He'll be odd. Different.

107
00:16:06,632 --> 00:16:11,137
He'll be fast. Virtually invulnerable.

108
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:15,057
Isolated, alone.

109
00:16:16,893 --> 00:16:18,060
[SIGHS]

110
00:16:18,227 --> 00:16:20,563
He will not be alone.

111
00:16:26,027 --> 00:16:28,529
He will never be alone.

112
00:16:37,205 --> 00:16:39,081
KRYPTONIAN:
The energy input to Jor-El's quarters...

113
00:16:39,248 --> 00:16:40,249
...is now in excess.

114
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:44,420
Our data indicates the loss
is due to a misuse of energy.

115
00:16:44,629 --> 00:16:45,922
Investigate.

116
00:16:46,589 --> 00:16:49,759
And if the investigation
proves correct?

117
00:16:51,761 --> 00:16:54,764
He knew the penalty he faced.

118
00:16:55,598 --> 00:16:57,600
He even is a member of this council.

119
00:17:00,102 --> 00:17:01,938
The law will be upheld.

120
00:17:43,646 --> 00:17:48,317
You will travel far, my little Kal-El.

121
00:17:49,652 --> 00:17:51,988
But we will never leave you...

122
00:17:52,697 --> 00:17:55,783
...even in the face of our deaths.

123
00:17:55,950 --> 00:18:01,956
The richness of our lives,
it will be yours.

124
00:18:02,498 --> 00:18:06,836
All that I have, all that I've learned,
everything I feel...

125
00:18:07,295 --> 00:18:09,839
...all this and more...

126
00:18:11,340 --> 00:18:14,176
...I bequeath you, my son.

127
00:18:16,846 --> 00:18:22,685
You will carry me inside you
all the days of your life.

128
00:18:24,020 --> 00:18:29,817
You will make my strength your own,
see my life through your eyes...

129
00:18:29,984 --> 00:18:33,029
...as your life will be seen
through mine.

130
00:18:35,531 --> 00:18:39,744
The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.

131
00:18:44,290 --> 00:18:46,375
This is all I...

132
00:18:48,628 --> 00:18:50,796
All I can send you...

133
00:18:51,797 --> 00:18:53,215
...Kal-El.

134
00:19:08,272 --> 00:19:11,901
[HIGH-PITCHED HUMMING]

135
00:19:16,906 --> 00:19:18,741
[EXPLOSIONS OUTSIDE]

136
00:19:41,889 --> 00:19:43,099
[HUMMING]

137
00:19:44,058 --> 00:19:46,227
[FLAMES ROARING]

138
00:20:12,044 --> 00:20:13,295
[CRASHING]

139
00:20:29,228 --> 00:20:31,230
[MACHINERY BEEPING]

140
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:36,986
[BEEPING FASTER]

141
00:21:13,606 --> 00:21:15,816
[SCREAMING]

142
00:21:27,536 --> 00:21:29,663
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

143
00:22:50,327 --> 00:22:52,288
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

144
00:23:02,298 --> 00:23:04,466
[SCREAMING]

145
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:07,887
ZOD:
Stop. Stop, stop!

146
00:23:11,473 --> 00:23:13,475
JOR-EL [OVER CRYSTAL]:
<i>--Which Einstein called...</i>

147
00:23:13,642 --> 00:23:14,810
<i>...his theory of relativity.</i>

148
00:23:14,977 --> 00:23:19,982
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

149
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:22,985
<i>...and scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...</i>

150
00:23:23,152 --> 00:23:26,405
<i>...spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

151
00:23:46,175 --> 00:23:51,055
<i>Early Chinese writings
point out the complex relationships..."</i>

152
00:23:53,349 --> 00:23:56,810
<i>By carrying this complex equation
to its ultimate power, my son...</i>

153
00:24:01,106 --> 00:24:03,442
<i>Chief among these powers
will be your sight...</i>

154
00:24:03,609 --> 00:24:05,527
<i>...your strength, your hearing...</i>

155
00:24:05,694 --> 00:24:10,532
<i>your ability to propel yourself
at almost limitless speed.</i>

156
00:24:10,699 --> 00:24:15,704
<i>The early history of our universe was
a bloody mosaic of interplanetary war.</i>

157
00:24:15,871 --> 00:24:18,791
<i>Each of the six galaxies
which you will pass through...</i>

158
00:24:18,958 --> 00:24:21,794
<i>...contain their own individual law,
space and time.</i>

159
00:24:21,961 --> 00:24:26,173
<i>It is forbidden for you
to interfere with human history.</i>

160
00:24:37,643 --> 00:24:39,853
[SIZZLING]

161
00:24:57,871 --> 00:24:59,081
[CRASHES]
[SCREAMS]

162
00:24:59,248 --> 00:25:00,916
What was that?

163
00:25:03,127 --> 00:25:04,211
[TIRE POPS]

164
00:25:24,398 --> 00:25:26,316
Now, wouldn't that beat all get-out?

165
00:25:26,483 --> 00:25:28,193
Will you-- You...

166
00:25:28,444 --> 00:25:29,486
Huh?

167
00:25:36,994 --> 00:25:38,120
Pa...

168
00:25:39,121 --> 00:25:40,956
Oh, my.

169
00:26:05,314 --> 00:26:06,607
[METAL CLANGS]

170
00:26:07,983 --> 00:26:09,818
[GRUNTING]

171
00:26:13,530 --> 00:26:15,616
All these years,
as happy as we've been...

172
00:26:15,783 --> 00:26:17,618
...how I've prayed the good Lord...

173
00:26:17,785 --> 00:26:20,329
...see fit to give us a child.

174
00:26:21,830 --> 00:26:24,333
Honey, will you hand me
that rag up there.

175
00:26:24,500 --> 00:26:26,001
You take things easy, Jonathan.

176
00:26:26,168 --> 00:26:28,754
Remember what Doc Frye said
about that heart of yours.

177
00:26:34,676 --> 00:26:38,639
Now the first thing we've got
to do when we get home is find out...

178
00:26:38,806 --> 00:26:40,849
...who that boy's proper family is.

179
00:26:41,850 --> 00:26:44,978
He hasn't got any.
Not around here, anyway.

180
00:26:48,774 --> 00:26:51,401
Martha, are you thinking
what I think you're thinking?

181
00:26:52,528 --> 00:26:56,698
We could say he's the child
of my cousin in North Dakota.

182
00:26:56,865 --> 00:26:58,200
And just now orphaned.

183
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:03,205
-Oh, Martha.
-Jonathan, he's only a baby.

184
00:27:03,372 --> 00:27:07,084
Martha...
Now, you saw how we found him.

185
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:13,382
Martha Clark Kent, are you
listening to what I'm saying?

186
00:27:14,216 --> 00:27:16,093
Jonathan!

187
00:27:45,372 --> 00:27:46,415
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

188
00:27:46,582 --> 00:27:48,333
Come on, gang.

189
00:27:49,418 --> 00:27:51,086
BOY 1:
Come on.

190
00:27:51,253 --> 00:27:53,922
BOY 2: That was a great game.
BOY 3: Yeah, but next week we're...

191
00:27:54,590 --> 00:27:56,258
GIRL 1:
All right.

192
00:27:57,426 --> 00:27:58,927
Come on, gang, hustle. Let's go.

193
00:27:59,094 --> 00:28:00,596
Stack your helmets neatly.

194
00:28:00,762 --> 00:28:03,765
Remember about those uniforms.
Cleaned and washed by tomorrow...

195
00:28:03,932 --> 00:28:05,976
...and looking like a football team.

196
00:28:06,143 --> 00:28:08,103
Clark, have the clothes
washed and ready...

197
00:28:08,270 --> 00:28:09,938
-...for tomorrow's game.
-Yes, sir.

198
00:28:10,105 --> 00:28:11,440
Got to beat Mount Vernon High!

199
00:28:11,607 --> 00:28:14,568
BOY 4: Can you give me a lift?
COACH: Home early!

200
00:28:19,781 --> 00:28:22,910
Lana? Don't bother with these, huh?

201
00:28:23,076 --> 00:28:25,787
I'll take them in with
the other equipment.

202
00:28:25,954 --> 00:28:28,790
-Thank you, Clark.
-Sure.

203
00:28:29,499 --> 00:28:32,294
Listen, a whole bunch of us
are going up to Mary Ellen's...

204
00:28:32,461 --> 00:28:34,129
...play some records...

205
00:28:34,880 --> 00:28:36,256
Would you like to come?

206
00:28:37,799 --> 00:28:40,928
Sure. Sounds like it'd be a lot of fun.

207
00:28:41,094 --> 00:28:43,764
Kent can't make it.
Still got a lot of work to do.

208
00:28:44,139 --> 00:28:46,975
What are you talking about?
I just finished stacking all the--

209
00:28:47,142 --> 00:28:48,518
-All that?
-Oh.

210
00:28:49,144 --> 00:28:50,979
Oh, Brad.

211
00:28:51,396 --> 00:28:55,108
GIRL 2: Hey, come on, Lana.
BRAD: Come on, Lana.

212
00:28:55,275 --> 00:28:56,985
Come on, let's go.

213
00:28:57,486 --> 00:28:59,154
-He's got to clean up.
-Bye, Clark.

214
00:28:59,321 --> 00:29:01,990
-Yeah. Bye, Lana.
-Clean this up, Clark.

215
00:29:03,450 --> 00:29:04,701
GIRL 3: Let's go.
GIRL 4: Bye, Clark.

216
00:29:04,868 --> 00:29:07,496
BOY 5: We're off to Mary Ellen's.
GIRL 4: See you, Clark.

217
00:29:08,163 --> 00:29:09,665
GIRL 3:
All right.

218
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:12,417
GIRL 4: Bye, Clark.
BOY 5: Bye, Clark.

219
00:29:12,584 --> 00:29:15,837
GIRL 3: Bye, Clark. See you tomorrow.
Bye-bye.

220
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:39,695
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

221
00:30:14,688 --> 00:30:16,732
Woo-hoo!

222
00:30:25,449 --> 00:30:28,744
Golly, I saw a boy out there
run as fast as the train!

223
00:30:28,952 --> 00:30:30,996
Faster even!

224
00:30:31,163 --> 00:30:34,583
Lois Lane, you have
a writer's gift for invention.

225
00:30:34,750 --> 00:30:36,752
-I'll say that for you.
-But-- But--

226
00:30:36,960 --> 00:30:40,213
Lois, please read your book.

227
00:30:40,589 --> 00:30:42,090
No one ever believes me.

228
00:30:55,979 --> 00:30:57,481
[TEENS CHATTERING]

229
00:31:01,777 --> 00:31:03,236
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO]

230
00:31:13,997 --> 00:31:16,041
Hey, look. There's Clark.

231
00:31:16,208 --> 00:31:18,543
BOY:
How come he's here?

232
00:31:18,710 --> 00:31:20,712
Clark.

233
00:31:20,879 --> 00:31:22,589
How'd you get here so fast?

234
00:31:23,632 --> 00:31:26,259
-I ran.
BRAD: Ran, huh?

235
00:31:26,426 --> 00:31:29,596
Told you he's an oddball.
Let's get out of here.

236
00:31:36,478 --> 00:31:39,022
Been showing off a bit,
haven't you, son?

237
00:31:46,905 --> 00:31:48,407
Uh...

238
00:31:51,326 --> 00:31:53,578
I didn't mean to show off, Pa.

239
00:31:57,040 --> 00:32:00,502
It's just that, guys like that Brad,
I just want to tear them apart.

240
00:32:00,669 --> 00:32:02,504
Yeah. I know.

241
00:32:02,671 --> 00:32:04,840
-Yeah, I know I shouldn't.
-Yeah, I know...

242
00:32:05,006 --> 00:32:07,008
...you can do
all these amazing things...

243
00:32:07,175 --> 00:32:09,845
...and sometimes you think
that you will just go bust...

244
00:32:10,053 --> 00:32:11,847
...unless you can tell people about it.

245
00:32:12,013 --> 00:32:14,850
Yeah. I mean, every time
I get the football...

246
00:32:15,016 --> 00:32:17,853
-...I can make a touchdown. Every time.
-That's for sure.

247
00:32:18,061 --> 00:32:20,522
I mean, is it showing off
if somebody's doing...

248
00:32:20,689 --> 00:32:24,359
...the things he's capable of doing?
Is a bird showing off when it flies?

249
00:32:24,526 --> 00:32:27,696
No. No, now you listen to me.

250
00:32:27,863 --> 00:32:30,031
When you first came to us,
we thought people...

251
00:32:30,198 --> 00:32:32,868
...would come take you away
because when they found out...

252
00:32:33,034 --> 00:32:36,705
...you know, the things you could do,
and that worried us a lot.

253
00:32:36,872 --> 00:32:39,708
Then a man gets older,
and he thinks very differently...

254
00:32:39,875 --> 00:32:42,627
...and things get very clear.

255
00:32:42,836 --> 00:32:44,671
And there's one thing I do know, son...

256
00:32:44,838 --> 00:32:48,216
...and that is you are here for a reason.

257
00:32:48,383 --> 00:32:50,844
I don't know whose reason,
but Whatever the reason...

258
00:32:51,011 --> 00:32:52,971
...maybe it's because...

259
00:32:56,725 --> 00:32:58,477
I don't know, it's...

260
00:33:00,228 --> 00:33:02,063
But I do know one thing:

261
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:04,900
It's not to score touchdowns.

262
00:33:05,192 --> 00:33:06,610
Huh?

263
00:33:07,235 --> 00:33:08,737
Thanks, Dad.

264
00:33:10,071 --> 00:33:11,990
I'll race you to it. Dad.

265
00:33:12,157 --> 00:33:14,159
-You Will, huh?
-Come on. Come on, Pop, run.

266
00:33:14,326 --> 00:33:16,495
Come on. Move. Move.
Yeah, go, go, go. Come on, run.

267
00:33:16,661 --> 00:33:17,704
[DOG BARKING]

268
00:33:17,871 --> 00:33:21,041
Hey, Baron! Hey, Baron. Hey, boy.

269
00:33:22,042 --> 00:33:24,085
[PANTING]

270
00:33:27,923 --> 00:33:29,841
Oh, no.

271
00:33:46,107 --> 00:33:47,776
Jonathan.

272
00:33:49,778 --> 00:33:51,947
Jonathan!

273
00:33:57,577 --> 00:33:59,037
Dad.

274
00:34:01,206 --> 00:34:02,582
MARTHA:
No!

275
00:34:05,961 --> 00:34:07,879
Jonathan!

276
00:34:09,965 --> 00:34:11,800
No!

277
00:34:49,671 --> 00:34:51,840
All those things I can do...

278
00:34:53,341 --> 00:34:55,427
All those powers...

279
00:34:58,096 --> 00:35:00,432
And I couldn't even save him.

280
00:35:48,772 --> 00:35:50,023
[RADIO CRACKLING]

281
00:36:01,785 --> 00:36:03,286
[CRACKLING STOPS]

282
00:36:06,831 --> 00:36:08,917
[WOLF HOWLS]

283
00:36:54,129 --> 00:36:56,589
[DOG BARKING]

284
00:37:45,513 --> 00:37:48,266
[ROOSTER CROWS]

285
00:37:59,986 --> 00:38:02,781
Clark, get up.

286
00:38:06,201 --> 00:38:08,495
Good morning, Smiley.

287
00:38:09,537 --> 00:38:12,207
Clark, breakfast.

288
00:38:15,460 --> 00:38:18,463
Are you gonna sleep all day?

289
00:38:19,506 --> 00:38:22,801
Clark, come on. Get up.

290
00:38:24,886 --> 00:38:26,304
[ROOSTER CROWS]

291
00:38:30,975 --> 00:38:33,061
[DOG BARKING]

292
00:39:22,777 --> 00:39:24,612
I have to leave.

293
00:39:30,451 --> 00:39:32,871
I knew this time would come.

294
00:39:33,705 --> 00:39:35,415
We both knew it...

295
00:39:35,582 --> 00:39:37,709
...from the day we found you.

296
00:39:48,428 --> 00:39:51,139
I talked to Ben Hubbard yesterday...

297
00:39:51,431 --> 00:39:57,645
...and he said that he'd be happy
to help out from now on.

298
00:40:04,152 --> 00:40:05,612
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

299
00:40:05,820 --> 00:40:07,405
Mother...

300
00:40:08,406 --> 00:40:10,408
I know, son.

301
00:40:12,118 --> 00:40:13,828
I know.

302
00:40:17,582 --> 00:40:21,044
Do you know where you're headed?

303
00:40:24,839 --> 00:40:26,341
North.

304
00:40:31,679 --> 00:40:33,681
Remember us, son.

305
00:40:35,516 --> 00:40:37,352
Always remember us.

306
00:42:47,148 --> 00:42:49,317
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

307
00:45:36,108 --> 00:45:38,486
[CRYSTAL WHINES]

308
00:46:13,854 --> 00:46:15,982
JOR-EL [OVER CRYSTAL]:
My <i>son...</i>

309
00:46:22,363 --> 00:46:24,824
<i>...you do not remember me.</i>

310
00:46:25,700 --> 00:46:27,493
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

311
00:46:28,536 --> 00:46:29,996
<i>I'm your father.</i>

312
00:46:32,456 --> 00:46:35,543
<i>By now, you will have reached
your 18th year...</i>

313
00:46:35,710 --> 00:46:38,379
<i>...as it is measured on Earth.</i>

314
00:46:38,546 --> 00:46:42,008
<i>By that reckoning,
I will have been dead...</i>

315
00:46:42,174 --> 00:46:45,428
<i>...for many thousands of your years.</i>

316
00:46:46,637 --> 00:46:49,056
<i>The knowledge...</i>

317
00:46:49,223 --> 00:46:52,810
<i>...that I have,
matters physical and historic...</i>

318
00:46:52,977 --> 00:46:57,189
<i>...I've given you fully on your voyage
to your new home.</i>

319
00:46:57,356 --> 00:47:02,737
<i>These are important matters, to be sure,
but still matters of mere fact.</i>

320
00:47:04,238 --> 00:47:07,074
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

321
00:47:07,241 --> 00:47:11,037
<i>And it is time for you to do so.</i>

322
00:47:12,872 --> 00:47:14,665
<i>Here in this...</i>

323
00:47:15,541 --> 00:47:18,961
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

324
00:47:19,754 --> 00:47:22,423
<i>...we shall try to find
the answers together.</i>

325
00:47:24,175 --> 00:47:26,761
<i>So, my son...</i>

326
00:47:26,969 --> 00:47:28,554
<i>...speak.</i>

327
00:47:29,597 --> 00:47:31,265
Who am I?

328
00:47:31,766 --> 00:47:33,934
<i>Your name is Kal-El.</i>

329
00:47:34,685 --> 00:47:38,439
<i>You are the only survivor
of the planet Krypton.</i>

330
00:47:38,773 --> 00:47:41,275
<i>Even though you've been
raised as a human being...</i>

331
00:47:41,484 --> 00:47:43,361
<i>...you are not one of them.</i>

332
00:47:43,986 --> 00:47:46,197
<i>You have great powers...</i>

333
00:47:46,364 --> 00:47:50,451
<i>...only some of which
you have as yet discovered.</i>

334
00:47:52,912 --> 00:47:54,455
<i>Come with me now, my son...</i>

335
00:47:54,622 --> 00:47:57,458
...as <i>we break through the bonds
of your earthly confinement.</i>

336
00:47:57,625 --> 00:48:01,128
<i>Traveling through time and space
in the six known dimensions.</i>

337
00:48:01,295 --> 00:48:04,632
<i>Your powers will far exceed
those of mortal men.</i>

338
00:48:04,799 --> 00:48:07,968
<i>It is forbidden for you to interfere
with human history.</i>

339
00:48:08,135 --> 00:48:11,806
<i>Rather, let your leadership
stir others to.</i>

340
00:48:13,140 --> 00:48:18,062
<i>In this next year, we shall
examine the human heart.</i>

341
00:48:18,229 --> 00:48:20,940
<i>It is more fragile than your own.</i>

342
00:48:21,107 --> 00:48:22,316
<i>For the past two years--</i>

343
00:48:22,483 --> 00:48:26,987
<i>As we pass through the flaming turmoil
which is the edge of your own galaxy...</i>

344
00:48:27,154 --> 00:48:29,490
<i>...we'll enter the realm
of the red Krypton sun...</i>

345
00:48:29,657 --> 00:48:32,326
<i>...source of your strength
and nourishment...</i>

346
00:48:32,493 --> 00:48:35,162
<i>...cause of our eventual destruction.</i>

347
00:48:36,163 --> 00:48:39,166
<i>The planet Krypton, my son.</i>

348
00:48:39,333 --> 00:48:42,753
<i>Your home, as it</i> was.

349
00:48:43,838 --> 00:48:47,967
<i>This year, we shall examine
the various concepts of immortality...</i>

350
00:48:48,134 --> 00:48:50,845
<i>...and their basis in actual fact.</i>

351
00:48:51,178 --> 00:48:55,766
<i>The total accumulation of all knowledge,
spanning the 28 known galaxies...</i>

352
00:48:55,933 --> 00:48:59,311
<i>...is embedded in the crystals
which I have sent along with you.</i>

353
00:48:59,478 --> 00:49:01,522
<i>Study them well, my son...</i>

354
00:49:01,689 --> 00:49:04,525
<i>...and learn from them.
We've reasoned out logical judgments.</i>

355
00:49:04,692 --> 00:49:08,028
<i>By the time you return
to the confines of your galaxy...</i>

356
00:49:08,195 --> 00:49:10,990
<i>...twelve of your years
will have passed.</i>

357
00:49:11,157 --> 00:49:16,120
<i>For this reason, among others,
I have chosen Earth for you.</i>

358
00:49:16,287 --> 00:49:19,540
<i>It is now time for you
to rejoin your new world...</i>

359
00:49:19,707 --> 00:49:23,502
<i>...and to serve its collective humanity.</i>

360
00:49:23,669 --> 00:49:26,130
<i>Live as one of them, Kal-El...</i>

361
00:49:26,297 --> 00:49:29,842
<i>...to discover where your strength
and your power are needed.</i>

362
00:49:30,009 --> 00:49:35,723
<i>Always hold in your heart
the pride of your special heritage.</i>

363
00:49:35,890 --> 00:49:39,226
<i>They can be a great people, Kal-El.
They wish to be.</i>

364
00:49:39,727 --> 00:49:42,897
<i>They only lack the light
to show the way.</i>

365
00:49:43,898 --> 00:49:48,194
<i>For this reason above all,
their capacity for good...</i>

366
00:49:48,736 --> 00:49:50,905
<i>...I have sent them you...</i>

367
00:49:52,406 --> 00:49:54,366
<i>...my only son.</i>

368
00:50:19,767 --> 00:50:22,269
[WHISTLE BLOWING]
[HORNS HONKING]

369
00:50:29,860 --> 00:50:33,113
CAB DRIVER:
Okay, this is it, mac, the <i>Daily Planet.</i>

370
00:50:33,280 --> 00:50:35,282
Fresh fruit. Hey, lady,
how about a tomato?

371
00:50:35,449 --> 00:50:37,409
Fresh fruit.
Hey, baby, how's it going?

372
00:50:37,576 --> 00:50:41,872
Hey, fresh fruit and vegetables.
They're so fresh...

373
00:50:42,623 --> 00:50:45,125
Fresh fruit and vegetables.
Get them while they're hot.

374
00:50:45,292 --> 00:50:47,878
Look at these tomatoes.
Aren't they beautiful?

375
00:50:48,087 --> 00:50:49,547
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

376
00:50:49,713 --> 00:50:51,131
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

377
00:50:53,259 --> 00:50:55,469
[PHONE RINGING]

378
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:03,310
He did a great job.
You see his article this morning?

379
00:51:12,069 --> 00:51:13,779
JIMMY:
Smile.

380
00:51:15,447 --> 00:51:18,826
-How many T's in "bloodletting"?
-Two.

381
00:51:24,832 --> 00:51:27,209
-What are you writing, Miss Lane?
-An ode to spring.

382
00:51:27,376 --> 00:51:29,461
-How do you spell "massacre"?
-Uh...

383
00:51:29,628 --> 00:51:33,882
-M-A-S-S-A-C-R-E.
-A...C...

384
00:51:34,049 --> 00:51:35,843
...R-E. Thank you.

385
00:51:36,010 --> 00:51:38,178
Golly, how come you get
all the great stories?

386
00:51:38,345 --> 00:51:40,639
A good reporter doesn't
get great stories, Jimmy.

387
00:51:40,806 --> 00:51:42,641
-A good reporter makes them great.
-Makes them great.

388
00:51:42,808 --> 00:51:44,476
Here's that story
on the East Side murder.

389
00:51:44,643 --> 00:51:47,688
I see it as a banner headline,
front page, maybe my picture--

390
00:51:47,855 --> 00:51:51,025
There's only one P in "rapist."
Lois Lane, say hello to Clark Kent.

391
00:51:51,191 --> 00:51:53,485
-Told you one P.
-Hello, Miss Lane. How are--?

392
00:51:53,652 --> 00:51:55,988
LOIS: Remember my exposé
on the sex and drug orgies...

393
00:51:56,155 --> 00:51:57,698
...in the senior citizens home?

394
00:51:57,865 --> 00:51:59,867
How you doing?
Jimmy Olsen, photographer.

395
00:52:00,034 --> 00:52:02,911
-Oh, hi. Clark Kent. Nice to meet you.
-Yeah.

396
00:52:03,078 --> 00:52:06,206
It's got everything. It's got sex,
violence, the ethnic angle--

397
00:52:06,373 --> 00:52:08,751
So does a lady wrestler
with a foreign accent.

398
00:52:08,917 --> 00:52:11,211
-Kent, can you open this?
-Oh, sure, Mr. White.

399
00:52:11,378 --> 00:52:13,047
This could be a series of articles:

400
00:52:13,213 --> 00:52:16,258
"Making Sense of Senseless Killings,"
by Lois Lane.

401
00:52:16,425 --> 00:52:19,011
We get psychologists, sociologists--

402
00:52:19,178 --> 00:52:22,723
Lois, you're pushing a bunch
of rinky-dink tabloid garbage.

403
00:52:22,890 --> 00:52:25,559
-The <i>Daily Planet</i> has a tradition--
-Oh, I'm sorry.

404
00:52:26,226 --> 00:52:29,271
Gosh, I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to shake it up like that.

405
00:52:29,438 --> 00:52:31,398
CLARK:
Oh, of course not, Lois.

406
00:52:31,565 --> 00:52:35,110
Why would anyone want to make
a total stranger look like a fool?

407
00:52:37,404 --> 00:52:39,782
-I'll take that.
-Oh, thank-- I'm sorry, Mr. White.

408
00:52:39,948 --> 00:52:43,702
Olsen, why am I paying you when
I should have you arrested for loitering?

409
00:52:43,869 --> 00:52:45,412
-Go get Mr... A towel.
-Kent.

410
00:52:45,579 --> 00:52:47,081
-Move, kid, move.
-Right, chief.

411
00:52:47,247 --> 00:52:49,083
-Make mine black, no sugar.
-Right, chief.

412
00:52:49,249 --> 00:52:51,710
-And don't call me sugar.
-"Blood is in Metropolis...

413
00:52:51,877 --> 00:52:53,921
-Right, sugar.
-...while the crocuses bloom."

414
00:52:54,088 --> 00:52:57,257
Chief wants coffee, no sugar.
I'll take tea with lemon.

415
00:52:57,424 --> 00:53:01,095
Lois, why don't you take Kent
out to meet everybody, huh?

416
00:53:01,261 --> 00:53:04,431
Just introduce him around.
He's starting with the paper today.

417
00:53:04,598 --> 00:53:06,058
I'm giving him the city beat.

418
00:53:06,767 --> 00:53:09,978
Chief, that's my beat.

419
00:53:10,145 --> 00:53:14,483
Lois, Clark Kent may seem like just
a mild-mannered reporter, but listen...

420
00:53:14,650 --> 00:53:18,112
...not only does he know how to treat
his editor in chief with respect...

421
00:53:18,278 --> 00:53:20,781
...not only does he have a snappy,
punchy prose style...

422
00:53:20,948 --> 00:53:24,827
...but he is, in my 40 years in this
business, the fastest typist I've seen.

423
00:53:24,993 --> 00:53:26,620
-That's great.
-Excuse me. I'm sorry.

424
00:53:26,787 --> 00:53:29,123
Here, you forgot my article.

425
00:53:31,125 --> 00:53:33,293
Oh, excuse me, Mr. White?

426
00:53:33,460 --> 00:53:36,755
I was wondering if perhaps
you could arrange for half my salary...

427
00:53:36,922 --> 00:53:39,800
...to be sent to this address
on a weekly basis.

428
00:53:39,967 --> 00:53:41,593
-Your bookie, right?
-My what?

429
00:53:41,760 --> 00:53:45,806
Don't tell me, he sends a check every
week to his sweet, gray-haired mother.

430
00:53:45,973 --> 00:53:47,975
Actually, she's silver-haired.

431
00:53:49,893 --> 00:53:51,478
Uh, I'll see what I can do.

432
00:53:51,645 --> 00:53:54,648
Uh, thank you very much, Mr. White.

433
00:53:54,982 --> 00:53:56,483
Excuse me.

434
00:53:58,444 --> 00:53:59,987
Well...

435
00:54:01,029 --> 00:54:02,614
Any more at home like you?

436
00:54:02,781 --> 00:54:04,908
Not really, no.

437
00:54:07,453 --> 00:54:09,455
I didn't think so.

438
00:54:10,497 --> 00:54:14,001
-Well, get yourself a desk over here.
-Over here?

439
00:54:14,168 --> 00:54:17,171
Yeah, right here.
There are some papers in a pile--

440
00:54:17,546 --> 00:54:20,507
Sorry. Excuse me.

441
00:54:35,522 --> 00:54:38,192
-Hi, Bill Breesen.
-Hi, Clark Kent.

442
00:54:38,358 --> 00:54:39,902
-Nice to meet you.
-Welcome aboard.

443
00:54:40,068 --> 00:54:41,195
Thank you.

444
00:54:41,361 --> 00:54:44,573
-Here's your towel, Mr. Clark.
-Um, Kent.

445
00:54:44,740 --> 00:54:45,824
-What?
-Kent.

446
00:54:45,991 --> 00:54:47,701
-Oh.
-Clark Kent.

447
00:54:47,868 --> 00:54:49,536
Jimmy Olsen.

448
00:54:53,165 --> 00:54:54,875
WOMAN: Yeah. It's fantastic.
LOIS: So you--?

449
00:54:55,042 --> 00:54:57,544
-I met this really great guy.
-Hey, fabulous.

450
00:54:57,711 --> 00:54:59,755
Yeah, fabulous.
I met him at this dude ranch.

451
00:54:59,963 --> 00:55:02,883
-Did--? I used to ride.
-Yeah, I haven't been since I was 7.

452
00:55:03,050 --> 00:55:06,053
-Oh, I gotta mail these letters.
-Okay, bye. Good luck tonight.

453
00:55:06,220 --> 00:55:07,721
-Oh, hi, Clark.
-Hi, Lois.

454
00:55:07,888 --> 00:55:09,723
How did you like your first day?

455
00:55:09,890 --> 00:55:13,435
Well, frankly, the hours
were sort of longer than I expected...

456
00:55:13,602 --> 00:55:17,064
...but on the whole, I mean, meeting you
and Jimmy Olsen and Mr. White...

457
00:55:17,231 --> 00:55:18,899
...gosh, I'd say it's been swell.

458
00:55:19,066 --> 00:55:21,568
-Swell?
-Yeah.

459
00:55:22,528 --> 00:55:27,074
You know, Clark, there are
very few people left in the world...

460
00:55:27,241 --> 00:55:29,409
...who feel comfortable
saying that word.

461
00:55:29,576 --> 00:55:30,911
-What word?
-"Swell."

462
00:55:31,078 --> 00:55:33,705
Really? I always thought
it was kind of natural.

463
00:55:34,289 --> 00:55:35,415
Ooh.

464
00:55:35,749 --> 00:55:38,043
-I'm sorry.
-Clark.

465
00:55:38,210 --> 00:55:39,795
MAN:
It's all right.

466
00:55:40,921 --> 00:55:42,256
-Sorry, Lois.
-Oh, hi, Rex.

467
00:55:42,422 --> 00:55:44,132
-Oh, Lois.
-See anything good today?

468
00:55:44,299 --> 00:55:45,884
-Not until you came along.
-Lois?

469
00:55:46,051 --> 00:55:47,761
-Oh, Rex, this is--
-Clark Kent.

470
00:55:47,928 --> 00:55:50,389
-Yeah, hi, see you around.
-Bye.

471
00:55:52,099 --> 00:55:55,018
-Lois?
-Hey, where you going?

472
00:55:55,185 --> 00:55:57,896
-Can I help you with your coat?
-Oh, yeah. Thanks.

473
00:55:58,438 --> 00:56:00,816
-So you like Mr. White.
-I thought he was a nice guy.

474
00:56:01,024 --> 00:56:03,610
-Jimmy Olsen was fantastic.
THUG: Hey, come here.

475
00:56:03,777 --> 00:56:06,280
Come on, come on. Get in here.
Hurry up. Come on.

476
00:56:06,446 --> 00:56:09,491
-We'd better get out of here.
-I think we'd better do what he says.

477
00:56:09,658 --> 00:56:12,786
-Come on, come on. Get in here, quick.
-Don't do anything.

478
00:56:12,953 --> 00:56:14,371
-That's it.
-We're coming.

479
00:56:14,538 --> 00:56:16,623
-Come on.
-We're coming. Excuse me.

480
00:56:16,790 --> 00:56:18,083
-Go on, back there.
-Here?

481
00:56:18,250 --> 00:56:20,127
Please don't point that at me, sir.

482
00:56:20,294 --> 00:56:22,629
-You could hurt somebody with that.
-Yeah, yeah.

483
00:56:22,796 --> 00:56:25,632
-Okay, okay, hold it there.
-Just a minute, mister.

484
00:56:25,799 --> 00:56:28,844
I realize of course that times
are tough for some these days...

485
00:56:29,052 --> 00:56:30,512
...but this isn't the answer.

486
00:56:30,679 --> 00:56:34,808
You can't solve society's problems
with a gun.

487
00:56:34,975 --> 00:56:39,146
You know something, buddy? You're
right. I'm gonna turn over a new leaf.

488
00:56:39,313 --> 00:56:42,482
Good for you, sir. That's the spirit.
He doesn't really want to hurt anybody.

489
00:56:42,649 --> 00:56:43,650
Uh-huh.

490
00:56:43,817 --> 00:56:46,653
-Right after I rip off this lady's purse.
-Of course.

491
00:56:46,820 --> 00:56:48,822
Now come on, lady, hand it over.

492
00:56:48,989 --> 00:56:51,658
Lois, I think maybe you better...

493
00:56:55,704 --> 00:56:58,206
CLARK:
Lois, what are you doing?

494
00:57:01,293 --> 00:57:02,836
[GRUNTING]

495
00:57:12,179 --> 00:57:14,640
Clark! Clark.

496
00:57:14,806 --> 00:57:18,018
Clark, are you all right? Clark!

497
00:57:18,185 --> 00:57:20,020
What happened?

498
00:57:20,312 --> 00:57:22,356
Golly. I guess I must have fainted.

499
00:57:22,522 --> 00:57:24,232
Fainted?

500
00:57:24,399 --> 00:57:27,027
-You fainted?
-Sorry.

501
00:57:38,705 --> 00:57:40,040
Swell.

502
00:57:40,207 --> 00:57:42,876
Really, Lois, supposing that man
had shot you?

503
00:57:43,043 --> 00:57:47,214
Is it worth risking your life over $10, two
credit cards, a hairbrush, and lipstick?

504
00:57:48,215 --> 00:57:50,717
-How did you know that?
-Know what?

505
00:57:51,677 --> 00:57:54,888
You just described the exact contents
of my purse.

506
00:57:55,639 --> 00:57:56,723
Hm.

507
00:57:57,265 --> 00:58:00,227
Um, wild guess.

508
00:58:03,230 --> 00:58:04,731
Taxi!

509
00:58:09,069 --> 00:58:11,530
-Hey.
-Hi, Otis.

510
00:58:21,748 --> 00:58:25,002
-So, what's happening, partner?
-Look what we got.

511
00:58:25,210 --> 00:58:27,587
-Let's take him.
-Wait a minute.

512
00:58:27,754 --> 00:58:30,590
Maybe he'll lead us
to the big man himself.

513
00:58:30,757 --> 00:58:34,219
-Lex Luthor?
-You got it, Armus.

514
00:58:34,761 --> 00:58:37,097
We'll make captain by midnight.

515
00:58:38,598 --> 00:58:40,308
Hey, what do you read?

516
00:58:40,475 --> 00:58:43,103
XK-101 rocket to be used.

517
00:58:43,270 --> 00:58:44,771
Hey, what do you read?

518
00:58:44,938 --> 00:58:46,565
-Hey, Matt.
-Hey, hey, Otis.

519
00:58:46,732 --> 00:58:48,942
Just getting the <i>Daily Planet</i> here.

520
00:58:49,901 --> 00:58:53,113
Hey, what do you read?
Down, down.

521
00:58:53,280 --> 00:58:54,990
Okay, okay.

522
00:58:55,198 --> 00:58:58,785
Okay. All right. See, I'm paying him.
I got a pretzel too.

523
00:58:58,952 --> 00:59:02,539
Thanks, Otis. Okay.
How many did he take, Shutzy?

524
00:59:05,375 --> 00:59:08,253
This is Metropolis 46. We're on foot.
Over and out.

525
00:59:08,420 --> 00:59:09,963
Let's go.

526
00:59:14,259 --> 00:59:16,470
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
<i>Your attention, please.</i>

527
00:59:16,636 --> 00:59:18,305
<i>Your attention, please.</i>

528
00:59:18,472 --> 00:59:21,933
<i>The Metropolis Flyer is now
ready for departure...</i>

529
00:59:22,100 --> 00:59:26,313
<i>...on the upper level, track six,
stopping at New Rochelle.</i>

530
00:59:26,480 --> 00:59:29,649
All right, he's going down to
the train platform. I'm going after him.

531
00:59:29,816 --> 00:59:32,277
Okay, Harry. I'll call for backup.
Be careful, now.

532
00:59:32,444 --> 00:59:34,821
-All right, Armus, all right.
WOMAN: All <i>aboard, please.</i>

533
00:59:36,656 --> 00:59:39,159
<i>Now boarding on the lower level--</i>

534
00:59:39,326 --> 00:59:41,620
MAN: Ten minutes, folks.
Come on, air-conditioned cars.

535
00:59:41,787 --> 00:59:44,164
Mount Vernon, Poughkeepsie,
Glen Corners.

536
00:59:44,331 --> 00:59:46,833
Aboard now. All aboard.
Metropolis Transportation.

537
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:50,504
Metropolis Transportation.
Buffalo, Syracuse.

538
00:59:50,670 --> 00:59:53,507
Smoking cars are forward.
Move along, now.

539
00:59:53,673 --> 00:59:55,092
Put your luggage up the top.

540
00:59:55,258 --> 00:59:58,929
Smoking cars forward.
All aboard. Boarding.

541
01:00:26,665 --> 01:00:29,334
Armus, Armus, make it track 22.

542
01:00:29,501 --> 01:00:33,672
I seen him, and I'm right on him.
Lower level, track 22.

543
01:00:33,839 --> 01:00:36,049
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

544
01:00:44,558 --> 01:00:46,518
[BELL DINGING]

545
01:01:10,041 --> 01:01:11,084
So that's it.

546
01:01:27,267 --> 01:01:31,271
LEX: It's amazing that brain can generate
enough power to keep those legs moving.

547
01:01:42,741 --> 01:01:44,743
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

548
01:01:51,041 --> 01:01:52,959
[HYDRAULICS HISS]

549
01:01:58,089 --> 01:02:00,133
[GRUNTING]

550
01:02:03,053 --> 01:02:04,387
[SCREAMS]

551
01:02:13,230 --> 01:02:14,773
Harry.

552
01:02:16,566 --> 01:02:19,653
Harry, where are you? Harry.

553
01:02:27,452 --> 01:02:28,995
Oh, no.

554
01:02:35,835 --> 01:02:37,379
Harry...

555
01:02:39,506 --> 01:02:41,132
Sick.

556
01:02:49,015 --> 01:02:52,936
-Sick. You're really sick.
-Sick, Miss Teschmacher?

557
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:56,356
Sick, when I'm mere days from executing
the crime of the century?

558
01:02:56,523 --> 01:02:59,484
No,no,no.
Step away from that, please.

559
01:03:00,777 --> 01:03:04,531
How do you choose to congratulate
the greatest criminal mind of our time?

560
01:03:05,156 --> 01:03:07,367
Do you tell me that I'm brilliant?
Oh, no, no.

561
01:03:07,534 --> 01:03:09,869
That would be too obvious,
I grant you.

562
01:03:10,036 --> 01:03:13,707
Charismatic. Fiendishly gifted.

563
01:03:14,374 --> 01:03:15,667
Try "twisted."

564
01:03:16,209 --> 01:03:17,210
[CHUCKLES]

565
01:03:21,423 --> 01:03:24,050
Get away from there.
Get away, get away, get away!

566
01:03:25,552 --> 01:03:27,053
Tell me something, Lex.

567
01:03:27,220 --> 01:03:30,140
Why do so many people have to die
for the crime of the century?

568
01:03:30,307 --> 01:03:32,058
Why? You ask why?

569
01:03:32,225 --> 01:03:35,228
Why does the phone always ring
when you're in the bathtub?

570
01:03:36,563 --> 01:03:40,483
Why is the most brilliantly
diabolical leader of our time...

571
01:03:40,650 --> 01:03:42,736
...surrounding himself
with total nincompoops?

572
01:03:42,944 --> 01:03:44,821
I'm back, Mr. Luthor.

573
01:03:44,988 --> 01:03:47,574
Yes, I was just talking about you.

574
01:03:48,074 --> 01:03:49,743
You were followed again.

575
01:03:53,913 --> 01:03:56,750
In spite of those catlike reflexes.

576
01:03:59,252 --> 01:04:02,589
Mr. Luthor. Mr. Luthor, I'm sorry.

577
01:04:02,756 --> 01:04:04,257
Otis.

578
01:04:05,216 --> 01:04:07,385
Is that the newspaper
I asked you to get me?

579
01:04:08,219 --> 01:04:09,429
Yeah.

580
01:04:10,096 --> 01:04:12,098
Why am I not reading it?

581
01:04:13,725 --> 01:04:15,685
Because I haven't given it to you yet?

582
01:04:15,852 --> 01:04:17,270
-Right.
-Oh.

583
01:04:22,025 --> 01:04:23,943
At last, it's official.

584
01:04:24,361 --> 01:04:27,614
Thanks to the government,
we will pull off...

585
01:04:27,781 --> 01:04:30,617
...the greatest real-estate swindle
of all time.

586
01:04:30,784 --> 01:04:33,203
Lex, what is this obsession
with real estate?

587
01:04:33,370 --> 01:04:35,288
All the time, "land, land, land."

588
01:04:35,455 --> 01:04:38,458
Miss Teschmacher, when I was
6 years old, my father said to me--

589
01:04:38,625 --> 01:04:39,876
"Get out."

590
01:04:41,127 --> 01:04:45,131
Before that. He said,
"Son, stocks may rise and fall.

591
01:04:45,298 --> 01:04:47,634
Utilities and transportation systems
may collapse.

592
01:04:47,801 --> 01:04:50,720
People are no damn good.
But they will always need land...

593
01:04:50,887 --> 01:04:53,139
...and they'll pay through the nose
to get it."

594
01:04:53,306 --> 01:04:55,141
"Remember," my father said...

595
01:04:55,308 --> 01:04:57,227
-Land.
-Right.

596
01:04:58,812 --> 01:05:02,482
It's a pity that he didn't see
from such humble beginnings...

597
01:05:02,649 --> 01:05:04,317
...how I've created this empire.

598
01:05:04,484 --> 01:05:05,985
An empire? This?

599
01:05:06,820 --> 01:05:09,322
Miss Teschmacher,
how many girls do you know...

600
01:05:09,531 --> 01:05:11,825
...who have a Park Avenue address
like this one?

601
01:05:11,991 --> 01:05:13,785
Park Avenue address?

602
01:05:13,952 --> 01:05:15,662
Two hundred feet below.

603
01:05:15,829 --> 01:05:18,498
Do you realize what people
are shelling out up there...

604
01:05:18,665 --> 01:05:21,668
...for a few miserable rooms
off a common elevator?

605
01:05:21,835 --> 01:05:24,629
TOGETHER:
What more could anyone ask?

606
01:05:30,301 --> 01:05:31,678
-Olsen!
JIMMY: Yeah?

607
01:05:31,845 --> 01:05:34,848
Get this Loch Ness update
right into Composing.

608
01:05:35,181 --> 01:05:38,935
Yeah? No, that's it, Roth.
Put it to bed. Right.

609
01:05:39,102 --> 01:05:42,147
-What are you standing around here for?
-I'm not--

610
01:05:42,313 --> 01:05:44,858
-I wasn't gonna say it.
-Go.

611
01:05:49,028 --> 01:05:51,531
-Ah, the sex maniac profile.
-Right.

612
01:05:51,698 --> 01:05:54,367
Look, 9-5 it's a Pulitzer Prize winner.
What do you bet?

613
01:05:54,534 --> 01:05:56,286
There's no Z in "brassiere."

614
01:05:56,453 --> 01:05:58,705
Hey, nice job
on that union scandal, Kent.

615
01:05:58,872 --> 01:06:01,040
Well, gosh, thanks, Mr. White.

616
01:06:03,960 --> 01:06:05,003
Uh...

617
01:06:05,170 --> 01:06:06,713
Oh, hi, Clark. Good night.

618
01:06:06,880 --> 01:06:09,632
-Here, let me carry that for you.
-Oh, thanks a lot.

619
01:06:09,799 --> 01:06:11,843
Lois, have you got a minute?

620
01:06:12,010 --> 01:06:14,220
Excuse me, please. Lois?

621
01:06:14,387 --> 01:06:17,724
And these two go to the addresses
on the envelope, okay?

622
01:06:17,891 --> 01:06:20,852
Lois, I was wondering if you
would like to have dinner with me?

623
01:06:21,019 --> 01:06:23,646
-Gosh, Clark, I'm sorry. I'm booked.
-Oh.

624
01:06:23,813 --> 01:06:26,691
Air Force One's landing at the airport
and this kid's there...

625
01:06:26,858 --> 01:06:30,528
...to make sure you-know-who answers
a few questions he'd rather duck.

626
01:06:30,695 --> 01:06:33,156
-My goodness, don't you ever let up?
-What for?

627
01:06:33,323 --> 01:06:36,242
I've seen how the other half lives.
My sister, for instance.

628
01:06:36,409 --> 01:06:39,412
Three kids, two cats,
and one mortgage. Yech.

629
01:06:39,621 --> 01:06:41,080
I would go bananas in a week.

630
01:06:41,247 --> 01:06:42,916
Oh, can I take you to the airport?

631
01:06:43,082 --> 01:06:45,335
Not unless you can fly.

632
01:06:45,877 --> 01:06:48,421
-Clark? Ladies.
-Sorry.

633
01:06:48,588 --> 01:06:51,925
-Change my clothes. Thank you. Bye.
-Hey, Lois, maybe we could--?

634
01:06:52,133 --> 01:06:53,635
[SIGHS]

635
01:06:55,386 --> 01:06:56,721
Um...

636
01:06:57,764 --> 01:06:59,182
Lois?

637
01:06:59,432 --> 01:07:04,103
-Would you be a pet and mail that?
-Oh, sure-- Good night.

638
01:07:05,271 --> 01:07:06,689
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

639
01:07:06,856 --> 01:07:07,899
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

640
01:07:08,066 --> 01:07:12,237
Oh. Going down, please. Going down.

641
01:07:15,114 --> 01:07:17,951
-Going down?
-Going up, up, up.

642
01:07:18,159 --> 01:07:19,452
[CHATTERING]

643
01:07:19,619 --> 01:07:21,120
Good night.

644
01:07:32,799 --> 01:07:34,634
<i>MAN</i> [OVER RADIO]: <i>Daily Planet Copter One, this is ground.</i>

645
01:07:34,801 --> 01:07:36,469
PILOT [OVER RADIO]: <i>Planet One,</i> go <i>ahead.</i>

646
01:07:36,678 --> 01:07:40,890
MAN: <i>We have Miss Lane for a ride to
Metropolis Airport to meet Air Force One.</i>

647
01:07:41,057 --> 01:07:43,309
PILOT: <i>Roger, we're on our way
and have you in sight.</i>

648
01:07:43,476 --> 01:07:45,645
<i>Have one aboard for transfer, over.</i>

649
01:07:45,812 --> 01:07:48,815
MAN: <i>Roger, Planet One. You're cleared.
Wind, 0-2-0 at 1-5, gusting.</i>

650
01:07:48,982 --> 01:07:52,819
<i>-Altimeter 2-niner-8-niner.
Roger, over and out.</i>

651
01:07:55,488 --> 01:07:57,323
[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]

652
01:08:44,370 --> 01:08:46,497
[RATTLING]

653
01:08:52,879 --> 01:08:54,797
A malfunction. Can't get liftoff.

654
01:08:54,964 --> 01:08:57,342
MAN: You <i>hooked</i> the <i>tail.</i>
-What's happening?

655
01:08:58,176 --> 01:08:59,510
<i>-Ah!
-Set it down.</i>

656
01:08:59,677 --> 01:09:03,056
Oh, my God! We've lost stabilizer
rotor control, I can't hold it!

657
01:09:08,394 --> 01:09:10,521
I can't hold it! I can't hold it!

658
01:09:13,650 --> 01:09:15,652
[SCREAMING]

659
01:09:28,039 --> 01:09:29,582
Wake up!

660
01:09:33,002 --> 01:09:34,379
Help!

661
01:09:34,545 --> 01:09:37,423
Help! Help!

662
01:09:38,883 --> 01:09:41,302
[TIRES SCREECHING]
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

663
01:09:43,513 --> 01:09:45,598
[LOIS GRUNTING]

664
01:09:48,101 --> 01:09:50,186
[SIRENS WAILING]

665
01:09:52,105 --> 01:09:54,273
Come on, step back. Step back, folks.

666
01:09:54,440 --> 01:09:57,610
All right, let's get back a little.
Move over across the street.

667
01:10:00,613 --> 01:10:02,281
Bring the cameras over here. Okay.

668
01:10:02,448 --> 01:10:04,951
Okay, you see the helicopter up there?

669
01:10:11,457 --> 01:10:12,959
Help me!

670
01:10:16,337 --> 01:10:18,089
[SHRIEKS]

671
01:10:20,883 --> 01:10:23,136
COP: All right, move back.
Let the ambulance through.

672
01:10:23,302 --> 01:10:25,138
WOMAN:
There's somebody in there!

673
01:10:28,641 --> 01:10:30,143
Help me!

674
01:10:32,979 --> 01:10:34,272
Ah!

675
01:10:35,231 --> 01:10:36,941
Okay. Come on, hold it. Get back.

676
01:10:37,108 --> 01:10:39,152
[SCREAMING]

677
01:10:40,653 --> 01:10:43,489
Come on. Come on, get off the streets.
Come on, get back.

678
01:10:43,656 --> 01:10:46,492
Move, let the firemen through.

679
01:10:46,659 --> 01:10:48,953
Boys, come on, now. Make a line.

680
01:10:54,459 --> 01:10:56,335
Move to the other side of the street.

681
01:10:57,670 --> 01:10:59,505
Come on. Get along.

682
01:10:59,672 --> 01:11:01,007
Get away from the building.

683
01:11:03,634 --> 01:11:05,803
Hold these crowds back. Move. Move.

684
01:11:08,181 --> 01:11:09,682
LOIS:
Help me!

685
01:11:15,313 --> 01:11:17,398
[HONKING]

686
01:11:25,364 --> 01:11:28,367
-Say, Jim, whoa!
-Excuse me.

687
01:11:28,534 --> 01:11:30,328
That's a bad outfit.

688
01:11:30,912 --> 01:11:33,498
-Woo!
-Okay, Bresslaw, move these people out.

689
01:11:42,924 --> 01:11:44,967
COP:
Oh, God, look up there.

690
01:11:46,385 --> 01:11:47,637
What the hell's that?

691
01:11:49,055 --> 01:11:51,182
-Oh!
-Easy, miss. I've got you.

692
01:11:51,349 --> 01:11:53,059
You-- You've got me?

693
01:11:53,226 --> 01:11:55,228
Who's got you?

694
01:11:55,937 --> 01:12:00,066
I can't believe it. I just cannot believe it.
He got her.

695
01:12:03,194 --> 01:12:04,362
[GASPING]

696
01:12:05,154 --> 01:12:06,823
[SCREAMS]

697
01:12:11,369 --> 01:12:12,662
[CHEERING]

698
01:12:44,777 --> 01:12:46,821
Gentlemen, this man needs help.

699
01:12:48,656 --> 01:12:52,660
Well, I certainly hope this little incident
hasn't put you off flying, miss.

700
01:12:53,619 --> 01:12:58,040
Statistically speaking, of course,
it's still the safest way to travel.

701
01:12:58,291 --> 01:13:00,751
Right. Wait.

702
01:13:05,673 --> 01:13:06,966
Who are you?

703
01:13:07,842 --> 01:13:09,176
A friend.

704
01:13:14,140 --> 01:13:16,058
Bye.

705
01:14:00,353 --> 01:14:01,604
[GRUNTING]

706
01:14:27,880 --> 01:14:30,424
Hi there. Something wrong
with the elevator?

707
01:14:30,675 --> 01:14:32,134
Ah!

708
01:14:37,890 --> 01:14:39,350
Going down.

709
01:14:46,065 --> 01:14:47,775
Nah...

710
01:14:51,404 --> 01:14:52,655
Officer.

711
01:14:56,200 --> 01:14:58,744
Good evening, Officer Mooney.

712
01:14:58,911 --> 01:15:01,747
Well, they say confession
is good for the soul.

713
01:15:03,082 --> 01:15:05,126
I'd listen to this man.

714
01:15:05,292 --> 01:15:07,086
Take him away.

715
01:15:11,757 --> 01:15:13,384
[TIRES SCREECH]

716
01:15:13,759 --> 01:15:15,052
[SIREN WAILING]

717
01:15:52,089 --> 01:15:53,632
Come on. Let's get out of here.

718
01:15:56,010 --> 01:15:57,636
[GUNFIRE IN DISTANCE]

719
01:16:03,934 --> 01:16:06,020
MAN 1:
Move your ass. Come on. Come on.

720
01:16:06,645 --> 01:16:08,647
Okay, let's go. Let's go.

721
01:16:08,814 --> 01:16:12,818
Drop your weapons.
Drop your weapons.

722
01:16:12,985 --> 01:16:14,820
Come on, let's get out of here.

723
01:16:14,987 --> 01:16:16,655
COP:
Okay, hold it. Hold it right there.

724
01:16:17,156 --> 01:16:18,824
-Freeze, you turkeys.
MAN 2: Don't shoot.

725
01:16:18,991 --> 01:16:20,659
MAN 3:
Be cool. You got us.

726
01:16:45,309 --> 01:16:47,019
Bad vibrations?

727
01:16:47,186 --> 01:16:50,356
Sergeant, you don't believe me.
I swear, flying.

728
01:16:50,523 --> 01:16:52,858
With a big red cape
and bright red boots, as well.

729
01:16:53,025 --> 01:16:55,194
-Watch the desk.
-Quick as a wink, he was gone.

730
01:16:55,361 --> 01:16:58,197
Flew up in the air again, he did,
like a big blue bird.

731
01:16:58,364 --> 01:17:00,157
-A blue bird...
-You don't believe me.

732
01:17:00,324 --> 01:17:02,034
-...with bright red boots.
-Flying.

733
01:17:02,201 --> 01:17:03,828
Take off, go back to Murphy's bar.

734
01:17:03,994 --> 01:17:06,038
-Continue what you started.
-Don't believe me.

735
01:17:06,205 --> 01:17:09,875
I'll be off in a few minutes
and I'll meet you there myself.

736
01:17:10,042 --> 01:17:11,794
[CROWD CLAMORING]

737
01:17:18,217 --> 01:17:21,720
Mooney, the first bottle's on me.

738
01:17:21,887 --> 01:17:23,389
Let me get my hat.

739
01:17:31,730 --> 01:17:33,065
[THUNDER CRASHES]

740
01:17:33,732 --> 01:17:36,026
GIRL: Hey, Frisky,
will you come down from there.

741
01:17:38,529 --> 01:17:40,239
Hi. I'll get him.

742
01:17:43,409 --> 01:17:44,702
[MEOWS]

743
01:17:44,869 --> 01:17:46,871
Come on. It's all right.

744
01:17:47,913 --> 01:17:49,582
Here you go, miss.

745
01:17:49,748 --> 01:17:52,418
-Gee, thanks, mister.
-Well...

746
01:17:53,419 --> 01:17:55,546
...goodbye, Frisky. So long, now.

747
01:17:59,133 --> 01:18:02,636
-Bye.
-Bye.

748
01:18:03,429 --> 01:18:06,140
Mommy, Mommy,
Frisky was stuck in the tree.

749
01:18:06,348 --> 01:18:09,268
This man swooped out of the sky
and gave him to me.

750
01:18:09,435 --> 01:18:12,646
MOM:
Haven't I told you to stop telling lies?

751
01:18:13,147 --> 01:18:15,399
[THUNDER CRASHING]

752
01:18:17,276 --> 01:18:19,612
Metropolis Airport,
this is Air Force One.

753
01:18:19,778 --> 01:18:22,323
-Could we have the weather report?
MAN: Roger, Air Force One.

754
01:18:22,489 --> 01:18:24,742
<i>Metropolis, currently
ceiling 500 overcast.</i>

755
01:18:24,909 --> 01:18:26,827
<i>700 broken,
visibility one half and showers.</i>

756
01:18:26,994 --> 01:18:29,622
<i>Wind 2-4-0 at 2-5,
altimeter niner-niner-eight.</i>

757
01:18:29,788 --> 01:18:31,290
Roger.

758
01:18:31,457 --> 01:18:33,876
Well, it doesn't look too good.
What do you think?

759
01:18:35,794 --> 01:18:37,630
-What the hell was that?
-What happened?

760
01:18:37,880 --> 01:18:39,131
We lost power in number one.

761
01:18:39,298 --> 01:18:41,133
Lost power? We lost the whole engine.

762
01:18:41,967 --> 01:18:43,969
-Shut down one.
-Pull one throttle closed.

763
01:18:44,136 --> 01:18:46,639
-Bring up 2 and 3.
-There's not enough pressure...

764
01:18:49,016 --> 01:18:52,311
Mayday, mayday, Metropolis tower.
Air Force One.

765
01:18:52,478 --> 01:18:55,814
We have lost port outboard engine
and part of wing.

766
01:18:55,981 --> 01:18:58,651
Request emergency landing.
What's the position?

767
01:18:58,817 --> 01:19:00,778
Ten miles southwest
of Metropolis Airport.

768
01:19:00,945 --> 01:19:03,322
-Notify them the president's on board.
-Position...

769
01:19:03,489 --> 01:19:06,367
...10 miles southwest
Metropolis Airport.

770
01:19:06,533 --> 01:19:10,329
Heading 3-0-5. Height, 6000 feet.

771
01:19:29,515 --> 01:19:32,184
What the hell happened?
We got our engine back?

772
01:19:32,351 --> 01:19:34,353
What the hell's going on out there?

773
01:19:34,520 --> 01:19:37,815
Fly. Don't look. Just fly.

774
01:19:37,982 --> 01:19:39,900
We got something.

775
01:19:40,067 --> 01:19:44,947
I ain't saying what it is. Just trust me.

776
01:19:56,000 --> 01:19:59,003
<i>JOR-EL:
You enjoyed it.</i>

777
01:20:01,547 --> 01:20:03,507
I don't know what to say, Father.

778
01:20:03,674 --> 01:20:05,551
I'm afraid I just got carried away.

779
01:20:06,593 --> 01:20:10,389
<i>-I anticipated this, my son.</i>
-You couldn't have.

780
01:20:10,556 --> 01:20:13,225
You couldn't have imagined...

781
01:20:13,726 --> 01:20:15,227
<i>How good it felt?</i>

782
01:20:17,730 --> 01:20:20,399
<i>You are revealed to the world.</i>

783
01:20:21,775 --> 01:20:24,236
<i>Very well. So be it.</i>

784
01:20:25,571 --> 01:20:28,907
<i>But you still must keep
your secret identity.</i>

785
01:20:29,074 --> 01:20:30,075
Why?

786
01:20:30,534 --> 01:20:32,536
<i>The reasons are two.</i>

787
01:20:32,703 --> 01:20:35,914
<i>First: You cannot serve humanity
28 hours a day.</i>

788
01:20:37,249 --> 01:20:39,752
<i>-24.
-Or 24...</i>

789
01:20:39,918 --> 01:20:43,255
<i>...as it is in Earth time.</i>

790
01:20:43,422 --> 01:20:45,924
<i>Your help would be
called for endlessly.</i>

791
01:20:46,091 --> 01:20:50,095
<i>Even for those tasks which human beings
could solve themselves.</i>

792
01:20:50,262 --> 01:20:53,974
<i>Because they're happy to abuse
their resources in such a way.</i>

793
01:20:54,141 --> 01:20:55,267
And secondly?

794
01:20:55,434 --> 01:20:56,602
<i>Second:</i>

795
01:20:56,769 --> 01:20:59,271
<i>Your enemies will discover...</i>

796
01:20:59,438 --> 01:21:01,607
<i>...their only way to hurt you:</i>

797
01:21:01,774 --> 01:21:04,109
<i>By hurting the people you care for.</i>

798
01:21:05,319 --> 01:21:06,612
Thank you, Father.

799
01:21:06,779 --> 01:21:08,739
<i>Lastly:</i>

800
01:21:10,407 --> 01:21:13,452
<i>Do not punish yourself
for your feelings of vanity.</i>

801
01:21:13,619 --> 01:21:15,454
<i>Simply learn to control them.</i>

802
01:21:15,913 --> 01:21:19,583
<i>It is an affliction common to all,
even on Krypton.</i>

803
01:21:19,750 --> 01:21:22,961
<i>Our destruction could have been avoided
but for the vanity of some...</i>

804
01:21:23,128 --> 01:21:26,298
<i>...who consider us indestructible.</i>

805
01:21:26,465 --> 01:21:29,301
<i>Were it not for vanity, why...</i>

806
01:21:29,676 --> 01:21:32,179
<i>...at this very moment...</i>

807
01:21:35,682 --> 01:21:38,644
<i>...I could embrace you in my arms...</i>

808
01:21:42,689 --> 01:21:44,149
<i>...my son.</i>

809
01:22:15,055 --> 01:22:17,015
<i>MAN [ON</i> TV]: <i>Reports are coming in of
a miraculous saving...</i>

810
01:22:17,182 --> 01:22:19,518
<i>-...of Air Force One...
MAN 2: A burglar was apprehended...</i>

811
01:22:19,685 --> 01:22:23,272
<i>-...by a man in a blue suit and red cape.
-...rescuing Miss Lois Lane...</i>

812
01:22:23,439 --> 01:22:26,358
<i>...Writer on the</i> Daily Planet,
<i>with one hand, and a...</i>

813
01:22:31,780 --> 01:22:34,783
Yeah, that'll be the day, huh?

814
01:22:34,950 --> 01:22:37,870
I said, that'll be the day
when a guy could fly, huh?

815
01:22:38,036 --> 01:22:41,165
Oh, I don't know.
You'd be surprised.

816
01:22:42,082 --> 01:22:44,835
-Yeah.
-Some <i>sort of fantastic hoax.</i>

817
01:22:45,002 --> 01:22:46,712
<i>Your guess is as good as anybody's.</i>

818
01:22:46,879 --> 01:22:49,173
<i>True or false, miracle or fraud?</i>

819
01:22:49,339 --> 01:22:51,508
<i>-The answer to that...</i>
LEX: Miss Teschmacher!

820
01:22:52,301 --> 01:22:54,052
Turn it off.

821
01:22:56,722 --> 01:22:58,724
[HAWAIIAN MUSIC PLAYS ON STEREO]

822
01:23:00,893 --> 01:23:04,855
Lex, what's the story on this guy?

823
01:23:05,022 --> 01:23:06,899
Do you think he's the genuine article?

824
01:23:07,065 --> 01:23:10,235
-If he is, he's not from this world.
—Why?

825
01:23:10,402 --> 01:23:13,572
If any human being were gonna
perpetrate such a fantastic hoax...

826
01:23:13,739 --> 01:23:15,616
...it would have been me.

827
01:23:18,869 --> 01:23:20,329
[GASPS]

828
01:23:24,416 --> 01:23:27,419
Otis! My robe!

829
01:23:29,546 --> 01:23:32,090
Right away, Mr. Luthor.

830
01:23:32,424 --> 01:23:36,595
It all fits somehow,
his coming here to Metropolis...

831
01:23:36,762 --> 01:23:39,139
...and at this particular time.

832
01:23:42,392 --> 01:23:44,895
There's kind of a cruel justice about it.

833
01:23:45,103 --> 01:23:46,939
To commit the crime of the century...

834
01:23:47,147 --> 01:23:50,567
...a man would just naturally want to
face the challenge of the century.

835
01:23:52,444 --> 01:23:56,406
Listen, Mr. Luthor, maybe this guy that
flies is just sort of passing through.

836
01:23:56,573 --> 01:23:58,951
-You know?
-Passing through?

837
01:23:59,159 --> 01:24:00,953
Not on your life, Otis...

838
01:24:01,119 --> 01:24:03,622
...which I would gladly sacrifice,
by the way...

839
01:24:03,789 --> 01:24:07,960
...for the opportunity of destroying
everything that he represents.

840
01:24:08,961 --> 01:24:10,796
And, Otis, by the way...

841
01:24:10,963 --> 01:24:14,466
...the next time, put my robe on
after I'm out of the pool.

842
01:24:14,633 --> 01:24:15,801
[GASPS]

843
01:24:16,051 --> 01:24:18,804
PERRY:
Now look. The <i>Post:</i> "It flies."

844
01:24:18,971 --> 01:24:21,306
The News: "Look, Ma, no wires."

845
01:24:21,473 --> 01:24:23,433
The <i>Times:</i> "Blue bomb buzzes
Metropolis."

846
01:24:23,600 --> 01:24:24,643
<i>The Planet:</i>

847
01:24:24,810 --> 01:24:27,813
We have the story of the century here.

848
01:24:27,980 --> 01:24:29,940
I want the name of
this whatchamacallit...

849
01:24:30,107 --> 01:24:32,276
...to go with the <i>Planet</i>
like bacon and eggs...

850
01:24:32,442 --> 01:24:35,404
...franks and beans, death and taxes,
politics and corruption.

851
01:24:35,571 --> 01:24:37,489
I don't think that
he would lend himself...

852
01:24:37,656 --> 01:24:39,658
...to any cheap promotion schemes,
Mr. White.

853
01:24:39,825 --> 01:24:41,285
Exactly how would you know that?

854
01:24:42,077 --> 01:24:43,412
Um...

855
01:24:44,329 --> 01:24:46,164
Just a first impression.

856
01:24:46,331 --> 01:24:48,917
Who's talking cheap?
I'll make him partner if I have to.

857
01:24:49,084 --> 01:24:50,627
-Right?
-Right, chief.

858
01:24:52,212 --> 01:24:53,672
I want the real story.

859
01:24:53,839 --> 01:24:56,174
I want the inside dope on this guy.

860
01:24:56,341 --> 01:25:00,012
Has he got a family? Where does he live?
What does the <i>S</i> stand for...

861
01:25:00,220 --> 01:25:02,514
LOIS: <i>"Tonight at eight. Your place.
Hopefully. A friend.</i>

862
01:25:02,723 --> 01:25:03,849
PERRY:
How does he fly?

863
01:25:04,016 --> 01:25:05,517
<i>A friend."</i>

864
01:25:08,812 --> 01:25:11,315
Tony, who is he?
Mike, what's his name?

865
01:25:11,481 --> 01:25:13,817
What's he got hidden under
that cape? Batteries?

866
01:25:13,984 --> 01:25:15,360
Why did he show up last night?

867
01:25:15,527 --> 01:25:17,696
Dick, where does he come from?

868
01:25:17,863 --> 01:25:19,156
Does he have a girlfriend?

869
01:25:21,700 --> 01:25:23,368
What's his favorite ball team, Kent?

870
01:25:23,535 --> 01:25:26,371
Now, listen to me.
I tell you, boys and girls...

871
01:25:26,538 --> 01:25:28,540
...whichever one of you
gets it out of him...

872
01:25:28,707 --> 01:25:31,627
...is gonna wind up with
the single most important interview...

873
01:25:31,793 --> 01:25:35,547
...since God talked to Moses.

874
01:25:38,383 --> 01:25:40,218
What are you standing
around about for?

875
01:25:40,385 --> 01:25:43,722
Move. Get on that story.

876
01:25:50,145 --> 01:25:51,396
[PHONE RINGS]

877
01:26:01,657 --> 01:26:04,076
"Eight o'clock," he says. 8:00, 8:00.

878
01:26:04,242 --> 01:26:05,744
Some friend.

879
01:26:06,536 --> 01:26:09,748
The story of my life.
Cinderella bites the dust.

880
01:26:22,094 --> 01:26:23,428
Good evening, Miss Lane.

881
01:26:26,014 --> 01:26:28,392
Uh, hi.

882
01:26:28,558 --> 01:26:30,602
Oh, I'm sorry,
did you have plans this evening?

883
01:26:30,811 --> 01:26:33,105
Oh. Oh, this old thing-- No.

884
01:26:33,271 --> 01:26:34,523
-It's no trouble...
-No.

885
01:26:34,690 --> 01:26:36,108
-...to come later.
-Don't move!

886
01:26:37,442 --> 01:26:39,569
Um... Or...

887
01:26:40,404 --> 01:26:42,239
Sure, you can move.

888
01:26:42,781 --> 01:26:44,574
Just don't fly away, all right?

889
01:26:45,450 --> 01:26:47,619
Sorry to drop in on you like this,
Miss Lane...

890
01:26:47,786 --> 01:26:50,205
...but there must be a lot
of questions about me...

891
01:26:50,372 --> 01:26:53,750
-...that people would like the answers to.
-Of course, yes.

892
01:26:59,339 --> 01:27:01,466
You really shouldn't smoke,
you know, Miss Lane.

893
01:27:02,634 --> 01:27:05,303
Don't tell me. Lung cancer, right?

894
01:27:07,472 --> 01:27:09,474
Well, not yet, thank goodness.

895
01:27:11,768 --> 01:27:14,312
Um, would you like a glass of wine?

896
01:27:14,479 --> 01:27:16,648
No, thanks. I never drink when I fly.

897
01:27:17,983 --> 01:27:19,317
Nice place.

898
01:27:19,484 --> 01:27:22,654
Oh, thank you. Thank you.

899
01:27:22,946 --> 01:27:25,741
Should we get started
with the interview?

900
01:27:27,492 --> 01:27:29,870
Oh. Thank you.

901
01:27:30,579 --> 01:27:33,790
Well, let's start
with your vital statistics.

902
01:27:33,957 --> 01:27:35,751
Are you married?

903
01:27:35,917 --> 01:27:37,502
No. No, I'm not.

904
01:27:38,378 --> 01:27:40,172
Do you have a girlfriend?

905
01:27:40,338 --> 01:27:44,342
No, I don't, but if I did, Miss Lane,
you'd be the first to know about it.

906
01:27:49,973 --> 01:27:52,100
Um, how old are you?

907
01:27:52,267 --> 01:27:54,686
-Over 21.
-Oh, I get it.

908
01:27:54,853 --> 01:27:56,688
You don't want anyone to
know how old-- Okay.

909
01:27:56,855 --> 01:27:59,524
How big are you? How tall are you?

910
01:27:59,691 --> 01:28:02,110
-About six-four.
-Six-foot-four.

911
01:28:02,277 --> 01:28:06,198
-And how much do you weigh?
-Around 2, 225.

912
01:28:06,782 --> 01:28:09,201
Two-- 225?

913
01:28:11,411 --> 01:28:12,788
Hm.

914
01:28:14,206 --> 01:28:18,502
Well, I assume, then, that...

915
01:28:18,877 --> 01:28:22,881
...the rest of your bodily functions
are normal?

916
01:28:23,548 --> 01:28:24,883
Sorry. I beg your pardon?

917
01:28:26,051 --> 01:28:28,220
Well, putting it delicately...

918
01:28:32,224 --> 01:28:34,142
...do you...

919
01:28:36,686 --> 01:28:41,566
-...eat?
-Yes. Yes, I do. When I'm hungry.

920
01:28:42,067 --> 01:28:45,237
You do. Of course you do.

921
01:28:45,403 --> 01:28:48,406
Well. Well, then, is it true...

922
01:28:48,573 --> 01:28:52,828
...that you can see through anything?

923
01:28:52,994 --> 01:28:55,497
Yes, I can. Well, pretty much.

924
01:28:55,664 --> 01:28:59,251
And that you're totally
impervious to pain?

925
01:28:59,417 --> 01:29:01,253
Well, so far.

926
01:29:02,212 --> 01:29:04,756
What color underwear am I wearing?

927
01:29:05,549 --> 01:29:06,842
Hm.

928
01:29:08,552 --> 01:29:10,595
-I'm sorry. I embarrassed you, didn't I?
-No.

929
01:29:10,762 --> 01:29:12,389
-I did.
-No, no. Not at all.

930
01:29:12,556 --> 01:29:15,767
It's just that this planter must be
made of lead.

931
01:29:15,934 --> 01:29:18,186
-Yes, it is. So?
-Oh, you see, I...

932
01:29:18,353 --> 01:29:20,564
...I sort of have a problem
seeing through lead.

933
01:29:21,273 --> 01:29:23,191
Oh, that's interesting.

934
01:29:23,358 --> 01:29:25,277
"Problems seeing through lead."

935
01:29:25,861 --> 01:29:29,072
-Do you have a first name?
-What, like "Ralph" or something?

936
01:29:29,239 --> 01:29:30,949
-No. I mean like--
-Pink.

937
01:29:31,116 --> 01:29:33,451
-Huh?
-Pink.

938
01:29:35,620 --> 01:29:38,081
I'm sorry, Miss Lane.
I didn't mean to embarrass you.

939
01:29:38,582 --> 01:29:40,917
You didn't embarrass me.

940
01:29:41,084 --> 01:29:43,128
Um... Uh...

941
01:29:43,295 --> 01:29:45,463
What's your background?
Where do you hail from?

942
01:29:46,798 --> 01:29:49,134
Well, that's kind of
hard to explain, actually.

943
01:29:49,301 --> 01:29:52,929
You see, I'm from...
Well, pretty far away.

944
01:29:53,096 --> 01:29:54,806
Another galaxy, as a matter of fact.

945
01:29:55,015 --> 01:29:57,475
-I come from a planet called Krypton.
-Huh?

946
01:29:57,976 --> 01:29:59,311
Krypton.

947
01:30:00,312 --> 01:30:04,816
Oh, Cripton. With a C-R-I...? No.

948
01:30:04,983 --> 01:30:08,612
No, actually, it's Krypton,
with a K-R-Y-P-T-O-N.

949
01:30:08,778 --> 01:30:13,658
K-R-Y... Do you like pink?

950
01:30:18,830 --> 01:30:21,249
I like pink very much, Lois.

951
01:30:25,170 --> 01:30:27,672
-Why are you--?
-I'm sorry?

952
01:30:28,173 --> 01:30:32,010
I mean, why are you here? There
must be a reason for you to be here.

953
01:30:32,177 --> 01:30:36,181
Yes. I'm here to fight for truth
and justice and the American way.

954
01:30:37,057 --> 01:30:40,185
You're gonna end up fighting
every elected official in this country.

955
01:30:40,352 --> 01:30:42,354
I'm sure you don't
really mean that, Lois.

956
01:30:42,520 --> 01:30:44,022
-I don't believe this.
-Lois?

957
01:30:44,189 --> 01:30:47,192
-Hm?
-I never lie.

958
01:30:48,693 --> 01:30:50,612
Oh.

959
01:30:51,571 --> 01:30:52,864
Um...

960
01:30:53,782 --> 01:30:55,033
Uh-- Oh.

961
01:30:55,200 --> 01:30:58,536
-Just how fast do you fly, by the way?
-I don't know, really.

962
01:30:58,703 --> 01:31:01,289
You know, I never actually
bothered to time myself.

963
01:31:01,456 --> 01:31:03,625
-No?
-Say...

964
01:31:04,709 --> 01:31:06,544
...why don't we find out?

965
01:31:06,711 --> 01:31:09,130
And how do you propose we do that?

966
01:31:09,297 --> 01:31:10,882
Take a ride with me?

967
01:31:11,049 --> 01:31:12,467
You mean I can fly?

968
01:31:12,634 --> 01:31:15,053
Actually, I'd be handling the flying,
if that's okay.

969
01:31:15,220 --> 01:31:18,390
-This is utterly fantastic.
-Wait a minute. Where are you going?

970
01:31:18,556 --> 01:31:20,725
-Are you serious?
-Sure.

971
01:31:21,518 --> 01:31:23,186
What's the matter, don't want to go?

972
01:31:23,353 --> 01:31:25,480
Okay. You don't need these.

973
01:31:25,647 --> 01:31:27,816
I need a sweater.
It must be kind of cold.

974
01:31:27,983 --> 01:31:29,818
You'll be warm enough.

975
01:31:35,907 --> 01:31:38,243
-Ready?
-Clark...

976
01:31:38,410 --> 01:31:42,747
...said that you're just a figment
of somebody's imagination...

977
01:31:42,914 --> 01:31:44,416
...like Peter Pan.

978
01:31:44,582 --> 01:31:47,168
Clark. Who's that, your boyfriend?

979
01:31:47,335 --> 01:31:49,421
Clark? Oh, Clark. No, he's nothing.

980
01:31:49,587 --> 01:31:50,880
-He's just a--
-Peter Pan, huh?

981
01:31:51,047 --> 01:31:52,424
Uh-huh.

982
01:31:53,258 --> 01:31:57,429
Peter Pan flew with children, Lois.
In a fairy tale.

983
01:32:03,685 --> 01:32:05,353
Ah!

984
01:32:07,772 --> 01:32:09,357
Oh!

985
01:32:15,071 --> 01:32:16,239
[GASPS]

986
01:34:53,062 --> 01:34:55,106
Oh! Ah!

987
01:34:58,067 --> 01:35:00,904
[SCREAMING]

988
01:35:13,625 --> 01:35:16,461
<i>LOIS:
Can you read my mind?</i>

989
01:35:20,632 --> 01:35:23,718
<i>Do you know what it is
that you do to me?</i>

990
01:35:26,304 --> 01:35:28,806
<i>I don't know who you are.</i>

991
01:35:33,811 --> 01:35:36,814
<i>Just a friend from another star.</i>

992
01:35:40,318 --> 01:35:43,738
<i>Here I am, like a kid out of school...</i>

993
01:35:44,614 --> 01:35:47,325
<i>...holding hands with a god.</i>

994
01:35:48,243 --> 01:35:49,994
<i>I'm a fool.</i>

995
01:35:51,329 --> 01:35:55,166
<i>Will you look at me, quivering.</i>

996
01:35:55,333 --> 01:35:58,169
<i>Like a little girl, shivering.</i>

997
01:35:58,503 --> 01:36:01,005
<i>You can see right through me.</i>

998
01:36:05,593 --> 01:36:08,304
<i>Can you read my mind?</i>

999
01:36:10,932 --> 01:36:13,685
<i>Can you picture
the things I'm thinking of?</i>

1000
01:36:18,189 --> 01:36:20,275
<i>Wondering why you are...</i>

1001
01:36:21,985 --> 01:36:24,195
<i>...all the wonderful things you are.</i>

1002
01:36:27,365 --> 01:36:29,033
<i>You can fly.</i>

1003
01:36:30,368 --> 01:36:32,036
<i>You belong in the sky.</i>

1004
01:36:34,205 --> 01:36:35,540
<i>You and I...</i>

1005
01:36:37,333 --> 01:36:39,711
<i>...could belong to each other.</i>

1006
01:36:42,213 --> 01:36:44,340
<i>If you need a friend...</i>

1007
01:36:47,385 --> 01:36:49,846
<i>...I'm the one to fly to.</i>

1008
01:36:53,808 --> 01:36:56,060
<i>If you need to be loved...</i>

1009
01:36:57,562 --> 01:36:59,564
<i>...here I am.</i>

1010
01:37:00,523 --> 01:37:02,567
<i>Read my mind.</i>

1011
01:37:24,005 --> 01:37:26,257
Oh, we forgot to time ourselves.

1012
01:37:26,466 --> 01:37:27,508
Uh-huh.

1013
01:37:27,675 --> 01:37:29,886
Oh, well, maybe next time.

1014
01:37:30,720 --> 01:37:31,763
Oh.

1015
01:37:39,020 --> 01:37:41,230
-You okay?
-Uh-huh.

1016
01:37:42,940 --> 01:37:45,401
Well, good night.

1017
01:37:45,777 --> 01:37:48,071
Oh, good night.

1018
01:37:52,700 --> 01:37:55,286
What a super man.

1019
01:38:00,792 --> 01:38:03,044
"Superman."

1020
01:38:03,211 --> 01:38:04,420
[KNOCKING]

1021
01:38:04,587 --> 01:38:07,215
CLARK:
Lois? Lois?

1022
01:38:07,382 --> 01:38:12,011
Anybody home? Hello? Lois?

1023
01:38:17,225 --> 01:38:20,269
-Hi. Can I come in?
-Oh, yeah.

1024
01:38:20,937 --> 01:38:23,481
Lois, for goodness' sake,
did you even hear me knocking?

1025
01:38:23,648 --> 01:38:24,816
Uh-huh.

1026
01:38:25,066 --> 01:38:28,444
Lois, we did have
a date tonight, remember?

1027
01:38:28,611 --> 01:38:29,821
Oh.

1028
01:38:30,321 --> 01:38:34,617
-Lois? You haven't been:
-Oh, no, no.

1029
01:38:34,784 --> 01:38:39,330
Well, I should certainly hope not.
Well, let's push off, shall we?

1030
01:38:39,497 --> 01:38:40,832
-I'd better get a coat.
-Okay.

1031
01:38:40,998 --> 01:38:43,960
It might be kind of cold out.
No, I mean...

1032
01:38:44,127 --> 01:38:47,755
...I need a purse, and I have to
fix my hair, and...

1033
01:38:47,922 --> 01:38:49,924
...put some blush on...

1034
01:39:05,773 --> 01:39:07,358
Lois...

1035
01:39:07,692 --> 01:39:11,028
...there's something I have to tell you.
I'm really--

1036
01:39:13,448 --> 01:39:18,286
I mean, I was, at first,
really nervous about tonight.

1037
01:39:18,703 --> 01:39:22,665
But then I decided, well, darn it, I was
gonna show you the time of your life.

1038
01:39:22,832 --> 01:39:24,876
That's Clark, nice.

1039
01:39:27,378 --> 01:39:30,047
I was thinking maybe we could
go for a hamburger, or...

1040
01:39:36,804 --> 01:39:38,389
LEX:
Now, then...

1041
01:39:39,390 --> 01:39:42,977
...given the exact location
of the galaxy that he mentions...

1042
01:39:43,144 --> 01:39:47,231
...and the proximity to our
own solar system...

1043
01:39:49,066 --> 01:39:50,985
...it's amazing.

1044
01:39:51,152 --> 01:39:53,905
Amazing. Too good to be true.

1045
01:39:54,071 --> 01:39:56,866
It's too good to be true.
He's 6'4", has black hair...

1046
01:39:57,033 --> 01:40:00,203
...blue eyes, doesn't drink,
doesn't smoke and tells the truth.

1047
01:40:00,369 --> 01:40:02,872
Miss Teschmacher, some people
read War and Peace...

1048
01:40:03,039 --> 01:40:05,917
...and come away thinking
it's a simple adventure story.

1049
01:40:06,083 --> 01:40:08,878
Others can read the ingredients
on a chewing gum wrapper...

1050
01:40:09,045 --> 01:40:11,631
...and unlock the secrets
of the universe.

1051
01:40:12,381 --> 01:40:16,260
Lex, what has chewing gum got to do
with the secrets of the universe?

1052
01:40:17,136 --> 01:40:18,513
[SIGHS]

1053
01:40:19,430 --> 01:40:21,432
Right. Right, Miss Teschmacher.

1054
01:40:21,682 --> 01:40:22,767
[SIGHS]

1055
01:40:24,560 --> 01:40:26,562
N, N, N...

1056
01:40:26,729 --> 01:40:29,440
M. You want M, Mr. Luthor?
Coming right up.

1057
01:40:30,858 --> 01:40:32,568
So there you go. M.

1058
01:40:32,735 --> 01:40:35,446
M, as in "moron," Otis?
No, no, no. It's N!

1059
01:40:35,613 --> 01:40:38,908
N, as in "Neanderthal,"
"nincompoop, nitwit."

1060
01:40:39,075 --> 01:40:41,953
-And L, as in "ladder"!
-Ladder, Mr. Luthor. Coming right up.

1061
01:40:42,119 --> 01:40:44,539
I didn't see, because I...

1062
01:40:44,705 --> 01:40:47,583
I'm sorry, Mr. Luthor. I-- Ooh!

1063
01:40:47,750 --> 01:40:51,963
In the interview, he says that
the planet Krypton...

1064
01:40:52,797 --> 01:40:55,633
...exploded in 1948.

1065
01:40:55,800 --> 01:41:00,805
Ridiculous little freak took three years
in a rocket ship to get to Earth.

1066
01:41:00,972 --> 01:41:06,435
-Ergo...
-Ergo. Ergo, 1948, three years...

1067
01:41:06,602 --> 01:41:07,979
He's 6'4", you know that?

1068
01:41:08,145 --> 01:41:11,816
Do you know why the number 200
is so vitally descriptive...

1069
01:41:11,983 --> 01:41:14,777
...to both you and me?
It's your weight and my IQ.

1070
01:41:14,944 --> 01:41:17,154
Now, think, people, think.

1071
01:41:18,072 --> 01:41:20,825
Deductive reasoning,
that's the name of the game.

1072
01:41:22,994 --> 01:41:27,456
Fragments from the planet Krypton
exploded and went into outer space.

1073
01:41:27,623 --> 01:41:31,669
It is reasonable to assume
that some of those particles of debris...

1074
01:41:31,836 --> 01:41:33,671
...drifted to Earth.

1075
01:41:35,590 --> 01:41:36,632
Meteorites.

1076
01:41:37,216 --> 01:41:38,676
[SPEAKS FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

1077
01:41:39,844 --> 01:41:41,846
Voilà!

1078
01:41:46,851 --> 01:41:48,019
Voilà.

1079
01:41:48,185 --> 01:41:50,354
Voilà.

1080
01:41:52,064 --> 01:41:54,859
A meteorite found in Addis Ababa?

1081
01:41:55,026 --> 01:42:00,031
Uh, I know I'm gonna get rapped
in the mouth for this, but so what?

1082
01:42:00,197 --> 01:42:03,909
So what? You mean, to us
they are just meteorites.

1083
01:42:04,076 --> 01:42:09,040
Fair enough. But the level
of specific radioactivity is so high...

1084
01:42:09,206 --> 01:42:12,752
...to anyone from the planet Krypton,
this substance is lethal.

1085
01:42:13,586 --> 01:42:15,421
Wait a minute, Mr. Luthor.

1086
01:42:15,588 --> 01:42:19,717
You mean fire and bullets
can't hurt this guy, but this stuff here...

1087
01:42:19,884 --> 01:42:22,261
ALL:
Will kill him.

1088
01:42:22,428 --> 01:42:23,763
-Oh.
-Oh.

1089
01:42:23,929 --> 01:42:25,431
Yeah, wow...

1090
01:42:25,598 --> 01:42:27,391
Doesn't it give you kind of...

1091
01:42:27,558 --> 01:42:31,604
...a shudder of electricity through you
to be in the same room with me?

1092
01:42:32,772 --> 01:42:35,900
Not like the one you'll get
when you try to lay that rock on him.

1093
01:42:36,067 --> 01:42:39,278
He can see you coming from miles
with those super peepers of his.

1094
01:42:39,445 --> 01:42:43,324
Oh, Lord, you gave them eyes,
but they cannot see.

1095
01:42:43,491 --> 01:42:45,868
Nor can Superman, through lead.

1096
01:42:47,620 --> 01:42:50,289
He can't see through lead.

1097
01:42:50,456 --> 01:42:52,625
And kryptonite will destroy him.

1098
01:42:56,003 --> 01:42:57,922
Any questions, class?

1099
01:42:58,964 --> 01:43:01,467
Wonder what they're wearing
in Addis Ababa.

1100
01:43:01,634 --> 01:43:03,094
Looks like a burnoose.

1101
01:43:03,260 --> 01:43:05,304
TESCHMACHER:
There's gold. It's 24 karat...

1102
01:43:05,471 --> 01:43:08,808
-Are we going to Addis Ababa?
-...not 18 karat gold.

1103
01:43:09,308 --> 01:43:11,644
<i>MAN</i> 1 [OVER RADIO]: <i>Mother Bird to missile convoy. Over.</i>

1104
01:43:11,811 --> 01:43:14,313
<i>MAN 2:
Missile convoy to Mother Bird, go ahead.</i>

1105
01:43:14,480 --> 01:43:17,274
<i>MAN 1:
Everything looks good. See you at base.</i>

1106
01:43:17,441 --> 01:43:21,612
<i>-Over and out.
-Roger, Mother Bird. Over and out.</i>

1107
01:43:28,452 --> 01:43:30,037
[MACHINERY BEEPING]

1108
01:43:34,500 --> 01:43:36,293
[TIRES SCREECH]

1109
01:44:04,697 --> 01:44:08,451
-Man, look at this.
-Looks pretty bad.

1110
01:44:10,828 --> 01:44:14,206
MAN 1: Think she's dead?
MAN 2: Better check her pulse.

1111
01:44:24,049 --> 01:44:25,885
All right, get an ambulance down here.

1112
01:44:26,051 --> 01:44:28,721
I don't wanna hold this convoy up
more than I have to.

1113
01:44:29,221 --> 01:44:31,932
She's having trouble breathing, sir.
What do you think?

1114
01:44:32,099 --> 01:44:34,560
Well, I suggest
vigorous chest massage.

1115
01:44:34,727 --> 01:44:37,396
If that doesn't work, mouth-to-mouth.

1116
01:44:37,563 --> 01:44:39,023
Yes, sir.

1117
01:44:39,190 --> 01:44:42,735
Sergeant, I won't have one of my men
doing anything I wouldn't do myself.

1118
01:44:42,902 --> 01:44:45,029
-Yeah, but, sir--
-Get an ambulance.

1119
01:44:45,196 --> 01:44:47,198
All right, men. Gather around.

1120
01:44:47,907 --> 01:44:49,992
About face!

1121
01:45:01,003 --> 01:45:02,588
[SIREN APPROACHES]

1122
01:45:17,228 --> 01:45:18,604
Hi.

1123
01:45:18,813 --> 01:45:20,147
Somebody hurt?

1124
01:45:36,247 --> 01:45:40,626
I did it. I did it, Mr. Luthor,
Miss Teschmacher.

1125
01:45:40,793 --> 01:45:44,088
-I did it, just like you told me.
-All right, Otis. All right.

1126
01:45:44,255 --> 01:45:48,092
All right, Otis. Listen,
it isn't that I don't trust you, but...

1127
01:45:48,259 --> 01:45:50,636
I don't trust you, Otis.
What did you do?

1128
01:45:50,803 --> 01:45:54,098
Well, I-- I set the first...

1129
01:45:54,265 --> 01:45:57,268
...directional vector to 38...

1130
01:45:57,434 --> 01:46:01,480
...the second one to 67,
and the third one to 117.

1131
01:46:01,647 --> 01:46:04,775
-What about the fourth one?
-What fourth one?

1132
01:46:04,942 --> 01:46:08,153
Now, wait a minute. Wait a minute.
The third one to 117?

1133
01:46:08,320 --> 01:46:10,698
Yes. See? I wrote it down, Mr. Luthor.
I wrote it--

1134
01:46:10,865 --> 01:46:13,117
Otis. Otis!

1135
01:46:13,284 --> 01:46:16,871
The third one was supposed to be 11,
and the fourth one, seven.

1136
01:46:17,079 --> 01:46:20,791
Oh. Well, gee, Mr. Luthor.

1137
01:46:20,958 --> 01:46:23,502
Oh, I see. I guess my arm
wasn't long enough, see?

1138
01:46:23,669 --> 01:46:26,213
Otis, would you like to see a long arm?

1139
01:46:26,380 --> 01:46:29,300
Otis, would you like to see
a very, very long arm?

1140
01:46:29,466 --> 01:46:32,678
-Oh, no, Mr. Luthor.
-Otis. Otis!

1141
01:46:32,845 --> 01:46:34,138
Ah!

1142
01:46:41,478 --> 01:46:43,355
[HONKING]

1143
01:46:43,814 --> 01:46:44,857
[SIREN WAILS]

1144
01:46:45,024 --> 01:46:48,819
-All right, get it right, will you?
-Yes, Mr. Luthor.

1145
01:46:49,320 --> 01:46:50,613
[HONKS]

1146
01:46:51,322 --> 01:46:53,991
McDonald, I thought you told me
this road was blocked off.

1147
01:46:54,158 --> 01:46:57,494
-Jablonski, you said it was blocked.
-I didn't ask him, I asked you.

1148
01:46:58,704 --> 01:47:01,332
All right, follow me. Follow me, men.

1149
01:47:02,041 --> 01:47:05,377
-Back that thing off the road.
-Back that thing up out of here.

1150
01:47:08,756 --> 01:47:11,592
You fellas get back into that thing
and back it off the road.

1151
01:47:11,759 --> 01:47:14,011
We got a convoy coming through here.

1152
01:47:15,554 --> 01:47:18,724
Listen, you're gonna have to circle back.
I don't have time to argue.

1153
01:47:18,891 --> 01:47:20,517
Heck of a day, isn't it?

1154
01:47:23,562 --> 01:47:27,733
LEX: We took the wrong turn.
We were looking for Route 12.

1155
01:47:27,900 --> 01:47:31,403
-Route 12? That's back there, isn't it?
-No, sir. It's up there.

1156
01:47:31,570 --> 01:47:33,113
[MEN CHATTERING]

1157
01:47:33,280 --> 01:47:37,076
-Sergeant, we took the wrong route.
-I'm a lieutenant, a naval officer.

1158
01:47:44,375 --> 01:47:46,043
MAN:
Shut up!

1159
01:47:46,210 --> 01:47:47,920
Route 12 is back that way.

1160
01:47:54,551 --> 01:47:56,387
LEX:
He's a diabetic...

1161
01:48:06,939 --> 01:48:09,483
LOIS: As you know, my newspaper,
the <i>Daily Planet...</i>

1162
01:48:09,692 --> 01:48:13,112
...is very interested in that dam,
but What I don't understand...

1163
01:48:13,278 --> 01:48:15,906
...is why you'd sell out
to a person you've never met.

1164
01:48:16,073 --> 01:48:18,283
I mean, you don't even
know his name. Oh, yeah.

1165
01:48:21,203 --> 01:48:23,956
MAN:
At the stupid-high price he offered...

1166
01:48:24,123 --> 01:48:28,794
...for this worthless piece of desert,
I hope it's Custer.

1167
01:48:30,462 --> 01:48:33,132
Perfect.
That's just what I need, thank you.

1168
01:48:33,298 --> 01:48:37,720
<i>[ON TV] Reporting live
from the launch site, ground zero.</i>

1169
01:48:38,095 --> 01:48:41,181
<i>Well, today marks an historic occasion.</i>

1170
01:48:41,348 --> 01:48:46,478
<i>Two XK 101 rockets
will be launched simultaneously...</i>

1171
01:48:46,645 --> 01:48:49,314
<i>...one by the Army and by the Navy.</i>

1172
01:48:49,481 --> 01:48:51,817
Hi, everybody. Has anybody
seen Lois around today?

1173
01:48:51,984 --> 01:48:54,153
GIL: No, I haven't, but the chief
wants to see you.

1174
01:48:54,319 --> 01:48:56,780
You're blocking the set, Clark.

1175
01:48:56,947 --> 01:49:00,826
Sorry, Gil. How's Judy today, okay?
Good? Great.

1176
01:49:00,993 --> 01:49:02,786
-Excuse me, Mr. White?
-Come in, Kent.

1177
01:49:02,953 --> 01:49:05,831
You wanted to see me?
Sir, have you seen Lois anywhere today?

1178
01:49:06,665 --> 01:49:09,001
She's out west looking into
a land fraud deal.

1179
01:49:09,251 --> 01:49:11,837
Sent young Olsen with her
on his first assignment.

1180
01:49:12,004 --> 01:49:15,174
Some unidentified clown out there
is buying up thousands of acres...

1181
01:49:15,340 --> 01:49:17,676
...of worthless desert
at incredible prices.

1182
01:49:17,843 --> 01:49:19,344
That doesn't seem to make sense.

1183
01:49:19,511 --> 01:49:22,473
The world doesn't make sense.
You ought to know that by now.

1184
01:49:22,639 --> 01:49:24,892
Look at this dispatch
from Addis Ababa.

1185
01:49:25,059 --> 01:49:28,145
People break into a museum
at night, kill two people...

1186
01:49:28,312 --> 01:49:30,898
...and what do they take?
A worthless piece of meteorite.

1187
01:49:31,065 --> 01:49:32,649
-How do you figure that?
-Well...

1188
01:49:32,816 --> 01:49:36,028
...frankly, I've never been able
to understand violence in any form.

1189
01:49:36,195 --> 01:49:40,324
I know that about you, Kent. That's one
of the reasons I wanted to talk to you.

1190
01:49:40,699 --> 01:49:44,078
I've been in this news game 40 years,
man and boy.

1191
01:49:44,286 --> 01:49:47,664
And I got where I am
with guts, compassion...

1192
01:49:47,831 --> 01:49:51,543
...elbow grease and something
you're sadly lacking in, son.

1193
01:49:51,794 --> 01:49:53,879
—Um, humility?
-No, not humility.

1194
01:49:54,046 --> 01:49:55,839
You got bags of humility.

1195
01:49:56,006 --> 01:49:58,425
Aggression, confidence,
that's the ticket.

1196
01:49:58,592 --> 01:50:00,552
Take charge. Let people know
who you are.

1197
01:50:00,719 --> 01:50:02,221
[HIGH-PITCHED FREQUENCY]

1198
01:50:02,429 --> 01:50:04,348
[DOGS BARKING]

1199
01:50:09,103 --> 01:50:11,230
LEX [OVER FREQUENCY]: <i>This</i> is Lex <i>Luthor.</i>

1200
01:50:11,396 --> 01:50:16,193
<i>Only one thing with less than four legs
can hear this frequency, Superman: You.</i>

1201
01:50:16,568 --> 01:50:19,029
<i>In approximately five minutes,
a poison gas pellet...</i>

1202
01:50:19,196 --> 01:50:21,865
... <i>containing propane-lithium
compound.</i> ..

1203
01:50:22,032 --> 01:50:24,868
<i>...will be released through
the city's air ducts...</i>

1204
01:50:25,035 --> 01:50:28,288
... <i>effectively annihilating
half the population of Metropolis.</i>

1205
01:50:28,455 --> 01:50:31,875
I was a reporter before
most of my friends were copy boys.

1206
01:50:32,042 --> 01:50:34,878
I want you to do that.
Get Lois to introduce you to Superman.

1207
01:50:35,045 --> 01:50:38,257
Find out who he is. What's he like?
Where'd he get that blue suit?

1208
01:50:38,423 --> 01:50:41,593
Did he have it made?
Is it silk? Is it plastic?

1209
01:50:41,760 --> 01:50:45,430
<i>I know it all seems a bit much,
but how else was I going to meet you?</i>

1210
01:50:45,597 --> 01:50:50,102
<i>I knew you'd never accept
an invitation to tea.</i>

1211
01:50:50,769 --> 01:50:56,400
<i>But a disaster, with people in danger,
people who need help...</i>

1212
01:50:56,567 --> 01:51:01,321
<i>...well, I just knew you couldn't resist
the chance to sort of pitch in.</i>

1213
01:51:01,488 --> 01:51:03,282
<i>Know what I mean?</i>

1214
01:51:20,924 --> 01:51:22,301
It's Superman.

1215
01:51:32,311 --> 01:51:34,021
-Look.
-Oh, my God!

1216
01:51:36,148 --> 01:51:40,152
<i>There's a strong streak of good
in you, Superman...</i>

1217
01:51:40,485 --> 01:51:43,155
<i>...but then, nobody's perfect.</i>

1218
01:51:45,449 --> 01:51:47,451
<i>Almost nobody.</i>

1219
01:51:55,167 --> 01:51:57,002
-What the--?
-Oh, Superman.

1220
01:51:57,169 --> 01:51:59,463
-Gee.
-Stand back, please. Stand back.

1221
01:51:59,630 --> 01:52:01,340
Nothing to get worried about.

1222
01:52:07,179 --> 01:52:08,847
Well, don't just sit there. Get out.

1223
01:52:22,819 --> 01:52:26,031
Look at that overgrown boy scout,
Miss Teschmacher.

1224
01:52:26,198 --> 01:52:27,324
Tell me what you see.

1225
01:52:28,492 --> 01:52:30,661
Cuteness, dimples.

1226
01:52:31,078 --> 01:52:33,330
You like cuteness, huh?

1227
01:52:33,497 --> 01:52:35,040
Dimples.

1228
01:52:35,207 --> 01:52:37,167
I'll give you dimples.

1229
01:53:11,285 --> 01:53:14,955
The pressure is still on you, Superman.
You know what they say:

1230
01:53:15,122 --> 01:53:18,208
"If you can't stand the heat,
get out of the tunnel."

1231
01:53:41,315 --> 01:53:43,775
This is your last chance, Superman.

1232
01:53:44,151 --> 01:53:47,571
<i>Why don't you do yourself
a flavor and freeze.</i>

1233
01:53:48,113 --> 01:53:50,073
[MACHINERY HUMS]

1234
01:54:06,548 --> 01:54:07,924
Yeah.

1235
01:54:29,654 --> 01:54:31,114
Hah.

1236
01:54:31,865 --> 01:54:33,367
[CRACKING]

1237
01:54:48,673 --> 01:54:50,092
I think he's coming, Mr. Luthor.

1238
01:54:58,183 --> 01:54:59,810
[CREAKING]

1239
01:55:00,852 --> 01:55:03,146
He's definitely coming, Mr. Luthor.

1240
01:55:14,699 --> 01:55:16,535
It's open. Come in.

1241
01:55:18,537 --> 01:55:21,832
My attorney will be in touch with you
about the damage to the door.

1242
01:55:21,998 --> 01:55:23,875
Otis, take the gentleman's cape.

1243
01:55:29,506 --> 01:55:33,051
-I don't think he wants me to.
-Luthor, where's the gas pellet?

1244
01:55:33,552 --> 01:55:35,011
Somewhere...

1245
01:55:36,721 --> 01:55:41,601
...in the back of my mind, actually.
It's a little idea I was toying with.

1246
01:55:41,768 --> 01:55:46,022
Is that how your warped brain gets its
kicks? Planning the death of innocents?

1247
01:55:46,731 --> 01:55:49,901
No, by causing the death
of innocent people.

1248
01:55:50,068 --> 01:55:51,653
<i>MAN 1:
Fire.</i>

1249
01:55:53,572 --> 01:55:56,741
<i>Navy Bird, we have a launch.</i>

1250
01:55:56,908 --> 01:56:00,287
<i>Navy missile, XK 101.</i>

1251
01:56:00,454 --> 01:56:01,913
<i>Angle of attack is perfect.</i>

1252
01:56:02,914 --> 01:56:06,251
<i>MAN 2: Climbing fast.
-Hydraulics, general function.</i>

1253
01:56:06,418 --> 01:56:10,464
Now, as you may or may not know,
I am, as they say...

1254
01:56:10,672 --> 01:56:13,091
...very heavy into real estate.

1255
01:56:13,258 --> 01:56:17,721
To make money in that game, you have
to buy for a little and sell for a lot, right?

1256
01:56:17,888 --> 01:56:20,140
-Right.
-Right.

1257
01:56:20,307 --> 01:56:23,101
So the problem:

1258
01:56:23,268 --> 01:56:26,104
How to make land more valuable
between the time you buy it...

1259
01:56:26,271 --> 01:56:28,273
...and the time you sell it.

1260
01:56:28,690 --> 01:56:33,403
Now, this is California, the richest,
most populous state in the union.

1261
01:56:33,570 --> 01:56:36,615
I don't need a geography lesson
from you, Luthor.

1262
01:56:36,781 --> 01:56:41,077
Oh, yes, of course, you've been there.
I do forget, you get around, don't you?

1263
01:56:41,244 --> 01:56:43,330
-Where was I?
-California.

1264
01:56:43,497 --> 01:56:47,083
California, right. The San Andreas Fault.
Maybe you've heard of it?

1265
01:56:47,250 --> 01:56:50,962
Yes. It's the joining of two land masses.
The fault line is unstable...

1266
01:56:51,129 --> 01:56:53,757
...which is why you get earthquakes
in California.

1267
01:56:53,924 --> 01:56:56,801
Wonderful.
Couldn't have said it better myself.

1268
01:56:57,219 --> 01:57:01,431
Everything west of this line
is the richest real estate in the world.

1269
01:57:01,598 --> 01:57:04,267
San Diego, Los Angeles, San Francisco.

1270
01:57:04,434 --> 01:57:09,147
Everything on this side is just hundreds
of miles of worthless desert land...

1271
01:57:09,314 --> 01:57:11,107
...which happens to be owned by...

1272
01:57:11,274 --> 01:57:12,275
[THWACK]

1273
01:57:12,442 --> 01:57:14,945
Lex Luthor, Incorporated.

1274
01:57:15,111 --> 01:57:19,491
Now, call me foolish,
call me irresponsible...

1275
01:57:19,658 --> 01:57:22,953
It occurs to me
that a 500-megaton bomb...

1276
01:57:23,119 --> 01:57:25,956
...planted at just the proper point,
would...

1277
01:57:26,122 --> 01:57:28,500
Would destroy most of California.

1278
01:57:29,626 --> 01:57:33,129
Millions of innocent people would die.
The West Coast as we know it would--

1279
01:57:33,296 --> 01:57:37,634
Fall into the sea. Bye-bye, California.

1280
01:57:37,801 --> 01:57:40,971
Hello, new West Coast.
My West Coast.

1281
01:57:43,348 --> 01:57:46,851
Costa del Lex, Luthorville,
Marina del Lex, Otisburg--

1282
01:57:49,813 --> 01:57:52,190
-Otisburg?
-Miss Teschmacher...

1283
01:57:52,357 --> 01:57:54,693
-...she's got her own place, Mr.--
-Otisburg?

1284
01:57:54,859 --> 01:57:57,862
-It's a little-bitty place.
-Otisburg?

1285
01:57:58,029 --> 01:58:01,032
Okay. I'll just wipe it off, that's all.
It's a little town.

1286
01:58:01,199 --> 01:58:04,411
You're a dreamer, Lex Luthor.
A sick, twisted dreamer.

1287
01:58:04,578 --> 01:58:06,871
Your plan couldn't possibly work.

1288
01:58:07,038 --> 01:58:12,168
I'll admit there were a few problems.
Adjusting the trajectory of the missile...

1289
01:58:12,335 --> 01:58:16,006
...finding the optimum stress point
for the fault line itself.

1290
01:58:16,172 --> 01:58:19,884
Which, by the way,
is target zero, right...

1291
01:58:20,510 --> 01:58:21,553
...here.

1292
01:58:21,886 --> 01:58:23,013
Ooh.

1293
01:58:30,186 --> 01:58:31,605
[HUMMING]

1294
01:58:46,703 --> 01:58:47,912
[CHATTERING]

1295
01:58:51,207 --> 01:58:54,085
-What's happening, lieutenant?
-Trajectory malfunction, sir.

1296
01:58:56,379 --> 01:58:59,090
-Then abort.
MAN: Yes, sir.

1297
01:59:04,721 --> 01:59:05,930
Function negative, sir.

1298
01:59:06,097 --> 01:59:08,933
-Can't you knock them down?
-Absolutely impossible, sir.

1299
01:59:09,100 --> 01:59:11,770
They have the new B-20 low-level
avoidance systems.

1300
01:59:11,936 --> 01:59:13,647
Get me the Pentagon.

1301
01:59:20,070 --> 01:59:23,615
Well, what do you think, Supe baby?
Interesting?

1302
01:59:23,782 --> 01:59:28,411
-Your theory's quite impressive, Luthor.
-Would you go to the viewing room?

1303
01:59:28,995 --> 01:59:31,956
But as for the rest,
it's nothing but a sick fantasy.

1304
01:59:32,123 --> 01:59:35,126
Fantasy? No. No.

1305
01:59:35,293 --> 01:59:38,296
It's history. It's happening, Superman.

1306
01:59:38,463 --> 01:59:40,131
Miss Teschmacher!

1307
01:59:44,803 --> 01:59:47,931
-Yes, Lex?
-Where's the rocket now?

1308
01:59:48,098 --> 01:59:51,810
It's going like a bat over the
Grand Canyon. So is the other one.

1309
01:59:51,976 --> 01:59:54,979
The other one? There's two of them?

1310
01:59:57,482 --> 02:00:00,485
Yeah, Superman. Double jeopardy.

1311
02:00:00,652 --> 02:00:03,613
Even you, with your great speed,
couldn't stop both of them.

1312
02:00:03,780 --> 02:00:07,283
While I, on the other hand,
could stop them with my detonator.

1313
02:00:07,450 --> 02:00:10,995
All right, Luthor. Where is it?
Where's the detonator?

1314
02:00:13,289 --> 02:00:14,999
[GRUNTS]

1315
02:00:24,843 --> 02:00:26,469
You diseased maniac.

1316
02:00:26,636 --> 02:00:29,806
Did you really think you could hide it
from me by encasing it in lead?

1317
02:00:29,973 --> 02:00:31,516
[GRUNTS]

1318
02:00:31,850 --> 02:00:35,854
-I'll mold this box into your prison bars.
-Don't touch that.

1319
02:00:42,444 --> 02:00:47,699
I told you. It's kryptonite, Superman.
A little souvenir from the old hometown.

1320
02:00:48,074 --> 02:00:51,202
I've spared no expense
to make you feel right at home.

1321
02:00:58,168 --> 02:01:02,756
You were great in your day, Superman.
But it just stands to reason...

1322
02:01:02,964 --> 02:01:05,175
...when it came time
to cash in your chips...

1323
02:01:05,341 --> 02:01:09,012
...this old, diseased maniac...

1324
02:01:09,179 --> 02:01:11,347
...would be your banker.

1325
02:01:14,476 --> 02:01:16,686
Mind over muscle.

1326
02:01:22,025 --> 02:01:23,485
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

1327
02:01:24,194 --> 02:01:28,782
You don't even care where
the other missile's headed, do you?

1328
02:01:28,990 --> 02:01:33,411
Certainly, I do.
I know exactly where it's headed.

1329
02:01:33,578 --> 02:01:35,246
Hackensack, New Jersey.

1330
02:01:35,705 --> 02:01:37,207
[GROANS]

1331
02:01:41,085 --> 02:01:43,797
I have to leave you now.
No hard feelings.

1332
02:01:44,005 --> 02:01:48,051
We all have our little faults.
Mine's in California.

1333
02:02:02,273 --> 02:02:06,277
Lex, my mother lives in Hackensack.

1334
02:02:16,120 --> 02:02:18,623
Miss Teschmacher!

1335
02:02:36,808 --> 02:02:38,476
<i>MAN</i> [OVER RADIO]: <i>Both birds uncontrolled.</i>

1336
02:02:38,643 --> 02:02:39,686
<i>Impossible to reset.</i>

1337
02:02:39,853 --> 02:02:41,938
[RADIO CHATTER CONTINUES]

1338
02:02:46,109 --> 02:02:47,610
LEX:
Otis.

1339
02:02:52,448 --> 02:02:54,284
[GASPS]

1340
02:03:06,129 --> 02:03:08,131
Miss Teschmacher.

1341
02:03:08,298 --> 02:03:10,174
Miss Teschmacher.

1342
02:03:11,843 --> 02:03:14,470
Please, you can't...

1343
02:03:14,637 --> 02:03:15,889
You can't just stand there.

1344
02:03:16,139 --> 02:03:18,099
Shh.

1345
02:03:19,475 --> 02:03:20,977
You can't just stand there...

1346
02:03:21,144 --> 02:03:23,980
...and let innocent people,
millions of innocent people, die.

1347
02:03:24,981 --> 02:03:26,691
Maybe.

1348
02:03:27,650 --> 02:03:30,153
Please. Please help me to save them.

1349
02:03:32,196 --> 02:03:34,699
If I help you, do you promise
to save my mother first?

1350
02:03:35,909 --> 02:03:37,994
But Lois and Jimmy...

1351
02:03:38,161 --> 02:03:39,537
Oh, but my mother comes first.

1352
02:03:39,704 --> 02:03:43,207
If you promise me, I'll believe you,
because you always tell the truth.

1353
02:03:45,543 --> 02:03:48,212
I promise. I promise.

1354
02:04:42,600 --> 02:04:45,186
Why did you kiss me first?

1355
02:04:46,270 --> 02:04:49,565
It-- I didn't think you'd let me later.

1356
02:04:50,566 --> 02:04:52,485
Thank you, Miss Teschmacher.

1357
02:04:52,694 --> 02:04:56,739
Why is it I can't get it on
with the good guys?

1358
02:05:01,703 --> 02:05:03,079
Stand aside, now.

1359
02:05:03,246 --> 02:05:04,914
I wouldn't stay here, either.

1360
02:05:23,474 --> 02:05:25,143
<i>MAN</i> 1 [OVER RADIO]: <i>Army bird still heading due east.</i>

1361
02:05:25,309 --> 02:05:28,771
<i>MAN 2: Navy bird still heading due west.
-Losing radar contact.</i>

1362
02:05:28,938 --> 02:05:30,982
<i>Next radar contact in 3 seconds.</i>

1363
02:05:31,149 --> 02:05:32,942
<i>--Intercept both birds.</i>

1364
02:05:52,503 --> 02:05:54,630
Army bird still headed east, sir.

1365
02:06:43,429 --> 02:06:44,680
[BEEPING]

1366
02:06:49,519 --> 02:06:51,854
MAN: <i>Army bird gaining altitude.</i>
-Miss Teschmacher.

1367
02:06:52,021 --> 02:06:55,066
<i>MAN 2: Radar contact strong.
-We have straight climb.</i>

1368
02:06:55,233 --> 02:06:57,235
Miss Teschmacher!

1369
02:06:57,401 --> 02:06:59,737
<i>Radar report,
Navy bird, San Andreas area.</i>

1370
02:06:59,904 --> 02:07:02,281
<i>Heading down.
Fifteen seconds to impact.</i>

1371
02:07:02,448 --> 02:07:04,909
<i>Navy bird heading down,
15 seconds to impact.</i>

1372
02:07:05,451 --> 02:07:07,036
<i>Fifteen seconds and counting.</i>

1373
02:07:09,539 --> 02:07:11,582
[MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO]

1374
02:07:16,212 --> 02:07:18,131
[HONKING]

1375
02:07:24,595 --> 02:07:26,639
MAN: <i>Impact: San Andreas.</i>
-God!

1376
02:07:55,001 --> 02:07:56,961
Mm.

1377
02:08:03,467 --> 02:08:05,428
NEWSMAN: <i>We interrupt the program
for a newsflash.</i>

1378
02:08:05,595 --> 02:08:08,931
<i>A military missile has exploded
in the Southern California desert.</i>

1379
02:08:09,098 --> 02:08:12,476
<i>The force of the explosion
has activated the San Andreas Fault.</i>

1380
02:08:12,643 --> 02:08:15,313
<i>California is suffering
a major earthquake.</i>

1381
02:08:22,445 --> 02:08:23,654
[CREAKING]

1382
02:08:23,905 --> 02:08:25,323
[CHATTERING]

1383
02:08:25,531 --> 02:08:27,700
[CARS HONKING]

1384
02:08:28,201 --> 02:08:29,952
[SCREAMING]

1385
02:08:56,145 --> 02:08:57,438
[BAAING]

1386
02:09:01,150 --> 02:09:02,985
MAN 1:
What's going on?

1387
02:09:04,820 --> 02:09:05,863
MAN 2:
It's a quake. Look!

1388
02:09:06,030 --> 02:09:07,990
[YELLING]

1389
02:09:17,041 --> 02:09:18,084
[TIRES SCREECH]

1390
02:09:19,961 --> 02:09:21,170
TEEN:
Look out!

1391
02:09:29,553 --> 02:09:30,972
[SHUDDERING]

1392
02:09:32,098 --> 02:09:33,724
DRIVER:
Get to the back of the bus!

1393
02:09:58,499 --> 02:10:00,543
[SCREAMING]

1394
02:10:14,390 --> 02:10:15,891
Okay, kids. It's all right now.

1395
02:10:16,058 --> 02:10:17,727
GIRL:
Thank God, we're back on the bridge.

1396
02:10:17,893 --> 02:10:20,271
-Hey, it's Superman.
BOY: It's Superman!

1397
02:10:27,236 --> 02:10:29,405
Holy mackerel!

1398
02:10:30,281 --> 02:10:31,407
MAN:
Going off the tracks!

1399
02:10:34,076 --> 02:10:35,411
Hang on!

1400
02:10:39,123 --> 02:10:40,249
I can't hold her!

1401
02:10:41,542 --> 02:10:42,835
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

1402
02:10:52,928 --> 02:10:54,347
[RUMBLING]

1403
02:11:00,269 --> 02:11:01,812
[ALARM WAILS]

1404
02:11:07,818 --> 02:11:09,653
<i>MAN</i> [OVER PA]: <i>All personnel, evacuate the dam.</i>

1405
02:11:09,820 --> 02:11:11,614
<i>All personnel, evacuate the dam.</i>

1406
02:11:12,281 --> 02:11:13,699
Ah!

1407
02:11:21,499 --> 02:11:23,292
WORKER 1:
Watch that cable!

1408
02:11:23,459 --> 02:11:24,960
My eyes! I can't see!

1409
02:11:30,633 --> 02:11:32,301
WORKER 2:
Someone try and pull the main!

1410
02:11:32,468 --> 02:11:34,678
WORKER 3:
It's impossible, it's red-hot!

1411
02:11:34,845 --> 02:11:36,305
[SCREAMING]

1412
02:11:41,685 --> 02:11:42,978
[POWERS DOWN]

1413
02:11:43,145 --> 02:11:45,523
-Gentlemen, is that man all right?
-Yeah.

1414
02:12:08,712 --> 02:12:11,549
-Ah--!
-Hang on, Jim.

1415
02:12:21,392 --> 02:12:22,560
MAN:
The dam burst!

1416
02:12:22,935 --> 02:12:26,021
Forget the car! Come on, come on!

1417
02:12:30,276 --> 02:12:32,236
You're safe here, son.

1418
02:12:33,404 --> 02:12:35,573
That's okay!
Miss Lane will be driving by soon.

1419
02:12:45,416 --> 02:12:47,460
-Come on, George.
MAN: Make for the hill.

1420
02:12:47,710 --> 02:12:49,170
[RUMBLING]

1421
02:12:54,425 --> 02:12:56,552
<i>MAN [ON</i> RADIO]: <i>There has been major quake damage...</i>

1422
02:12:56,719 --> 02:12:57,720
<i>...to Southern California.</i>

1423
02:12:57,887 --> 02:13:00,431
<i>The San Andreas Fault
has miraculously sealed itself...</i>

1424
02:13:00,598 --> 02:13:03,893
<i>...yet Southern California is suffering
major aftershocks of a major earthquake.</i>

1425
02:13:04,059 --> 02:13:05,102
[ENGINE SPUTTERS]

1426
02:13:05,269 --> 02:13:07,271
<i>The population is warned
to be aware of...</i>

1427
02:13:09,565 --> 02:13:10,774
Please, come on, turn over.

1428
02:13:10,941 --> 02:13:12,902
<i>-Which in some areas has--
-Come on!</i>

1429
02:13:15,571 --> 02:13:17,239
[GASPS]

1430
02:13:17,448 --> 02:13:18,908
[SCREAMS]

1431
02:13:40,471 --> 02:13:42,306
Help me. Help me.

1432
02:13:47,478 --> 02:13:49,271
[SCREAMING]

1433
02:14:53,168 --> 02:14:55,212
[GRUNTING]

1434
02:15:00,092 --> 02:15:01,802
[COUGHING]

1435
02:15:34,043 --> 02:15:35,085
[COUGHING]

1436
02:15:36,754 --> 02:15:37,880
[MOUTHS]
<i>Lois.</i>

1437
02:15:53,937 --> 02:15:55,731
[GROANS]

1438
02:18:33,806 --> 02:18:36,809
<i>No, no, no...</i>

1439
02:18:37,810 --> 02:18:40,646
No... No...

1440
02:18:40,813 --> 02:18:42,898
[SCREAMS]

1441
02:18:52,032 --> 02:18:53,283
[THUNDER CRASHING]

1442
02:18:53,450 --> 02:18:55,410
JOR-EL:
My <i>son.</i>

1443
02:18:55,619 --> 02:18:58,622
<i>It is forbidden for you to interfere
in human history.</i>

1444
02:18:58,789 --> 02:19:04,086
JONATHAN: <i>One thing I do know, son,
and that is you are here for a reason.</i>

1445
02:19:04,253 --> 02:19:07,297
<i>-It is forbidden for you to interfere...
CLARK: Those things I can do...</i>

1446
02:19:07,464 --> 02:19:10,801
<i>...all those powers,
and I couldn't even save him.</i>

1447
02:19:10,968 --> 02:19:12,636
<i>JOR-EL:
It is forbidden.</i>

1448
02:19:15,097 --> 02:19:17,266
<i>It is forbidden.</i>

1449
02:20:19,995 --> 02:20:21,330
[ENGINE SPUTTERS]

1450
02:20:42,225 --> 02:20:43,685
Hi.

1451
02:20:45,062 --> 02:20:46,521
Don't bother, I think it's dead.

1452
02:20:48,440 --> 02:20:50,525
Sure it's dead.

1453
02:20:51,652 --> 02:20:55,030
The problem with Men of Steel, there's
never one around when you want one.

1454
02:20:55,197 --> 02:20:57,532
Know what happened to me
while you were off flying?

1455
02:20:57,699 --> 02:20:59,242
I was almost in an earthquake...

1456
02:20:59,409 --> 02:21:01,411
...I had this gas station blow up...

1457
02:21:01,578 --> 02:21:03,956
...there's telephone poles
falling all over...

1458
02:21:04,164 --> 02:21:06,917
...I'm almost killed,
and to top the whole thing off...

1459
02:21:07,084 --> 02:21:08,710
...this stupid car runs out of gas!

1460
02:21:08,877 --> 02:21:10,754
I'm sorry about that, Lois...

1461
02:21:10,921 --> 02:21:13,090
...but I've been kind of busy
for a while.

1462
02:21:15,717 --> 02:21:18,178
I'm sorry. That's all right.

1463
02:21:27,896 --> 02:21:29,398
JIMMY:
Hey!

1464
02:21:29,982 --> 02:21:31,233
Thanks a lot, Superman.

1465
02:21:31,608 --> 02:21:34,236
You put me in the middle of nowhere
during an earthquake.

1466
02:21:34,403 --> 02:21:36,446
No food, no water, snakes everywhere.

1467
02:21:36,613 --> 02:21:39,282
-I had no idea if you were coming back--
BOTH: Jimmy.

1468
02:21:39,449 --> 02:21:40,492
[MUFFLED SPEAKING]

1469
02:21:40,701 --> 02:21:43,954
Listen, there's something I have to do.
I'll see you later.

1470
02:21:46,289 --> 02:21:48,750
He can't stay still for a second.

1471
02:21:49,918 --> 02:21:51,962
Oh. Golly, Miss Lane...

1472
02:21:52,129 --> 02:21:54,256
...it's too bad Mr. Kent
didn't see all this.

1473
02:21:54,423 --> 02:21:55,924
Yeah, poor Clark.

1474
02:21:56,091 --> 02:21:58,093
He's never around when S--

1475
02:21:58,427 --> 02:21:59,803
Clark-- Wait a minute.

1476
02:21:59,970 --> 02:22:01,763
-Wait a minute.
-What?

1477
02:22:03,306 --> 02:22:05,600
Lois Lane, that is the silliest idea ever.

1478
02:22:05,767 --> 02:22:09,479
Let me tell you something, Miss Lane,
I think he really cares about you.

1479
02:22:09,646 --> 02:22:11,773
-Clark? Of course he does.
-No, not Clark.

1480
02:22:14,317 --> 02:22:18,947
Oh, well, Superman cares
about everybody, Jimmy.

1481
02:22:19,322 --> 02:22:23,660
<i>But, who knows, someday,
you know, if he's lucky....</i>

1482
02:22:30,250 --> 02:22:32,044
[ALARM WAILS]

1483
02:22:35,964 --> 02:22:37,632
LEX:
You're messing up my suit.

1484
02:22:37,799 --> 02:22:39,509
You big lummox, you.

1485
02:22:39,676 --> 02:22:41,803
Come on, stop it, will you.

1486
02:22:41,970 --> 02:22:44,514
Otis, it's your fault.
Watch the ground!

1487
02:22:45,307 --> 02:22:46,641
Good evening, warden.

1488
02:22:46,808 --> 02:22:48,560
These two men should be safe here...

1489
02:22:48,769 --> 02:22:51,146
-...until they can get a fair trial.
-Who is it?

1490
02:22:53,565 --> 02:22:55,150
Lex Luthor!

1491
02:22:55,317 --> 02:22:58,028
-The greatest criminal mind of our time!
OTIS: Of our time!

1492
02:22:58,195 --> 02:22:59,821
-I hereby serve notice...
-Notice.

1493
02:22:59,988 --> 02:23:01,698
-...that these walls--
-These walls here...

1494
02:23:01,865 --> 02:23:03,033
Will you shut up, please.

1495
02:23:03,200 --> 02:23:04,701
All right, take them away, boys.

1496
02:23:04,868 --> 02:23:07,329
-You nitwit. Nincompoop!
OTIS: Guard, guard...

1497
02:23:07,496 --> 02:23:11,541
This country is safe again, Superman,
thanks to you.

1498
02:23:11,708 --> 02:23:13,794
No, sir. Don't thank me, warden.

1499
02:23:14,419 --> 02:23:16,588
We're all part of the same team.

1500
02:23:16,797 --> 02:23:18,298
Night.

1501
02:31:21,656 --> 02:31:23,658
[ENGLISH - us - SDH]

